Title: b'Get Big Trucker Arms Workout With The Healthy Trucker'
Description:
b"http://www.thehealthytrucker.net/

Workout with dumbbells to get big arms as a truck driver!

View related blog post here: 
http://www.thehealthytrucker.net/3-dumbbell-curl-exercises-for-truckers

Join Derek from The Healthy Trucker as he shows us how we can tone up and improve on our biceps, even as truckers that spend a lot of time on the road. Derek breaks down three different variations on the bicep curl that can be done easily on the road: the standard curl, the hammer curl, and the gorilla curl. Each variation works a separate part of the bicep, and done together, will yield results similar to those glorious peaks Arnold Schwarzenegger used to tote around as a bodybuilder (although maybe not that big). Just remember, as a truck driver making his way across the country, your health is your responsibility. We're here to give you tips and hints to make being responsible on the road a little bit easier.

Derek focuses in on some workout and exercise routines that can be easily performed out on the road with little or no equipment needed. This series is dedicated to you, the trucker out there that is concerned about his health or who is looking to improve it. We will give you exercise tips and advice that will help you to stay healthy as a trucker out on the road and hopefully help to improve your quality of life. 

Visit our website for more free driver exercises and healthy living tips: www.TheHealthyTrucker.net

Title: b"Strongmen Competitors' BROLY Traps || Can you train a muscle every day marathon || ep 13"
Description:
b'SUMMARY: another case of every day stimulus (not annihilation) resulting in ridiculous muscle adaptation through growth. these guys are constantly doing pulling, carrying, and overhead movements that stimulate the trapezius complex to a massive extent. deadlifts, stoneloading, farmer carries, hercules' pillars etc. in order to make it in this sport, you NEED strong traps. and before the steroid comments come pouring in (because there IS some drug use in the sport), remember that 

1) many sports use massive doses of anabolic steroids, but NONE compare to the overall trapezius development of strongmen competitors. olympic lifters are a close second. pro bodybuilders, except for a few, dont even come close (even though they juice just as much if not more).

2) the steroids they use simply "add" to the size of their traps...without them, i can guarantee you they would still have above average trap development. all the natty guys i kno who trained traps every day have massive traps.

3) this is just one case out of many (just look at the episode number), so unless u assume that everyone else on this series is on the juice (yea...the ballerinas, me, hanzah, mohamed, alex, ola, tayo, the construction workers, the charcoal motherfuckers etc etc etc), the steroid argument is blatantly invalid. dominate your day fellas.

Title: b'Poi Tutorial: Barrel Roll Turn Around (4 Petal, 2 demonstration only)'
Description:
b"This lesson is a quick break down of the 4 petal barrel roll turn around. This is not to be confused with barrel rolls used for inversion work. Instead, this move is modeled after the dance move where the artist moves as if they are rolling over a barrel as they turn. The poi stay in the same plane the duration of the pattern and they remain on the wall plane between the artist and the audience. 

The lesson explains the 4 petal turn around and then demonstrates 2 petal variations at the end. 

This lesson is brought to you by Isa GlitterGirl Isaacs, founder of the world's first poi fire dancing academy, Temple of Poi (http://templeofpoi.com ) founded in 2002.

Title: b'Dylan Wentz at WABDL 2009 World Championships in Reno'
Description:
b"PLEASE READ
World Association of Benchers and Deadlifters World Championships 2009 in Reno, Nevada.
Only my second competition ever, after WABDL Nationals 2009 in Portland, OR. Deciding to compete in this competition was iffy, and finally realizing how huge of an opportunity and that it's one of those things that not many people get to do, 2 weeks out I finally decided to do it haha. That being said, with not much time to prep for this comp, I am very satisfied with my efforts and results. I weighed in at 214lbs, and was at the time of the competition and currently am 18 years old. I competed in Class 1 Men's and Teen Men 18-19 Years Old, both in the 220lb weight class. Fortunately my lifts from the first day I lifted rolled over to the day of the second division, so I didn't have to lift again and was able to go home after the few days that I could afford to stay. Though my opener on bench was intended to be raw (without a shirt), I unfortunately was only able to warm up with a few reps of 225 and a handful of pushups. Pretty good cold opener, eh? Next to that, I lost weight since my shirt was sized and wasn't even used to lifting in it, so it wasn't as tight as it should be and didn't workout to well on my final attempt. Of course, I don't blame that on the shirt. All the more reason to train harder in the gym ;D I didn't deadlift as much as I should have either, even the judges said I should have attempted more as my final lift looked too easy haha. I was hesitant to even make a 2nd attempt though because despite the ease of my opener, I ended up holding my breath and almost gave myself a hernia. I'm glad I took the risk though, and got myself a new PR along with it.
Results: 4th place in bench and 2nd place in deadlift for Class 1 Men's 220lb. Then, World Champion in both bench and deadlift for Teen Men 18-19 Year Old 220lb weight class, along with a best lifter award.
All credit goes to our Heavenly Father for the passion and gifts He's given me for this sport, His Son who gave it all that we may live in this wonderful day, and of course Gus Rethwisch for giving me this amazing opportunity.
Special Thanks in the beginning is a bit blurry, so this is what they say: Our Father in Heaven, and His Son. My loving family. Gus Rethwisch, WABDL Founder & President, AJ Geldersma, Edward Yeager, Larry Vincent, Dusty Watson, ...and my bunny!
SONGS ARE PROPERTY OF THEIR RIGHTFUL OWNERS AND PRODUCERS. I DO NOT CLAIM ANY PROPERTY OVER THEM AT ALL.
Intro song- Misanthropes by Viatrophy.
2nd song clip- Not I by Demon Hunter
3rd song clip- Twilight of the Thunder God by Amon Amarth (sped up a bit for timing effects).

Thanks again for watching!"

Title: b'Como Ganar Masa Muscular Rapidamente - Que Hacer Para Ganar Musculo Rapido'
Description:
b'Haz Clic Aqui: http://tinyurl.com/CuerpoPerfecto

Si usted es un hombre flaco que busca ganar masa muscular r\xc3\xa1pidamente, hay algunas cosas que usted debe hacer para crecer los musculos y ponerte grande. Aqu\xc3\xad est\xc3\xa1n mis consejos para ganar la masa muscular y la construcci\xc3\xb3n de un gran cuerpo, sin convertirse en una rata del gimnasio.

1 / Progresivo de Sobrecarga

Este es el verdadero secreto para ganar masa muscular r\xc3\xa1pidamente y la construcci\xc3\xb3n de un cuerpo fuerte y duro. En resumen, se tiene que aumentar progresivamente el r\xc3\xa9gimen de formaci\xc3\xb3n, el aumento de la carga que levantar a medida que progresas en tus entrenamientos. Sus m\xc3\xbasculos responden a la estimulaci\xc3\xb3n y se adaptan y crecen para satisfacer el aumento de la carga. Si la presi\xc3\xb3n se mantiene igual que no se desarrollar\xc3\xa1n m\xc3\xa1s ... \xc2\xbfpor qu\xc3\xa9 lo har\xc3\xadan? Aumentar la carga y que responda, que es mucho m\xc3\xa1s cierto.

Para ganar masa muscular r\xc3\xa1pidamente el n\xc3\xbamero ideal de repeticiones es entre 8 y 12, con el n\xc3\xbamero de sets alrededor de 1-3. Si est\xc3\xa1 haciendo m\xc3\xa1s que esto, entonces su peso es demasiado ligero, si est\xc3\xa1 haciendo menos de que est\xc3\xa1n demasiado pesados y probablemente usted no est\xc3\xa1 obteniendo el m\xc3\xa1ximo beneficio de la estimulaci\xc3\xb3n muscular y la intensidad.

2 / Comer, Comer, Comer ... y luego comer algo m\xc3\xa1s!

Aparte de hecho entrar en un gimnasio y levantar algunas pesas, la dieta es la mayor raz\xc3\xb3n la gente lucha para ganar masa muscular r\xc3\xa1pidamente. Si no come lo suficiente no se puede esperar cualquier crecimiento. Muchas de las prote\xc3\xadnas, los bloques de construcci\xc3\xb3n de la masa muscular, es cr\xc3\xadtica para el \xc3\xa9xito en sus esfuerzos de ganar m\xc3\xbasculo. Idealmente se debe consumir un m\xc3\xadnimo de 3.000 calor\xc3\xadas por d\xc3\xada, divididos entre 5 o 6 comidas, compuesto de 40% carbohidratos, 25% de prote\xc3\xadnas, y 25% las grasas buenas. Las buenas grasas ayudar\xc3\xa1 a aumentar los niveles de hormonas anabolizantes en su cuerpo, el fomento de r\xc3\xa1pida ganancia muscular.

3 / Comprender Sus Niveles Hormonales

La mayor\xc3\xada de la gente que busca la manera de ganar masa muscular r\xc3\xa1pido abandono de entender el papel que juegan sus hormonas en la capacidad de su cuerpo de el m\xc3\xbasculo y crecerlo r\xc3\xa1pido.

En t\xc3\xa9rminos generales, podemos dividir las hormonas en dos grupos - anab\xc3\xb3licos y catab\xc3\xb3licos.

Hormonas anabolizantes (en forma de testosterona, hormona de crecimiento, y factores de crecimiento del insulina) ayudan a nuestros m\xc3\xbasculos a crecer, mientras que las hormonas catab\xc3\xb3licas (cortisol, progesterona, y la adrenalina) contribuyen a la degradaci\xc3\xb3n de prote\xc3\xadnas del m\xc3\xbasculo, que se utilizar\xc3\xa1 para la glucosa (energ\xc3\xada) s\xc3\xadntesis. Por lo tanto, en otras palabras, demasiadas hormonas catab\xc3\xb3licas realmente puede ser perjudicial para nuestros intentos de ganar masa muscular r\xc3\xa1pidamente, ya que puede llegar a deshacer nuestro duro trabajo.

Como reducir naturalmente los niveles de la hormona catab\xc3\xb3lica

a) Evitar el estr\xc3\xa9s lo m\xc3\xa1s posible en su vida - el estr\xc3\xa9s produce la adrenalina que es una hormona catab\xc3\xb3lica.

b) Obtener el descanso y el sue\xc3\xb1o suficiente entre los entrenamientos para reducir los niveles de cortisol

c) Consumir una dieta rica en prote\xc3\xadnas para reducir los niveles de cortisol'

b"Sudesh Peris wins a Silver medal at the Commonwealth for weightlifting
Anton Sudesh Peiris Kurukulasooriyage (born February 3, 1985) is a weightlifter from Sri Lanka. Kurukulasooriyage was born in Sandalankawa, Sri Lanka.
Sudesh Peiris has won the Silver Medal for Men's weightlifting in the 62kg category at the Commonwealth Games 2014 in Glasgow. Peiris's medal is Sri Lanka's first medal at these games.
Peiris is also the Captain of the Sri Lankan contingent at these games and was the country's flag bearer at the opening ceremony.
He had won the Bronze Medal in the Men's 62kg clean and jerk category at the previous Commonwealth Games in Delhi back in 2010."

Title: b'Deadlifts from Blocks - Deadlift Variation Using Blocks for Peak Performance'
Description:
b"http://www.bodyperformance.net/ Deadlifts from blocks - Deadlift Variation Using Blocks for Peak Performance

Kevin Weiss from Body Performance.net this is the last deadlift variation I am going to film and then I will move onto 

other exercises and exercise variations. So this is deadlift from blocks... we have done deadlift from deficit where you 

are standing on the blocks to raise you up so the bar is lower then it normally would be so this is esentially the 

opposite where I have set the barbell up on some platforms so it's about 4 inches up off the ground and that puts the bar 

at about mid shin level or just below the knee level as opposed to if you were in the regular bottom position that puts 

you about mid shin or slightly below. So you use this variation with people that are maybe just starting learn the deadlift 

or are having flexibility issues and they can't get themselves down into the proper position when they try and get down 

to the bar and if they're not flexible enough in the hamstrings and stuff they'll start to round as they try and get down into 

that position and so by bringing the bar up a little bit higher for them to get them started off you can get them pulling 

from a proper position and you then as you increase their strength and flexibility you can get them down to the proper 

position and it usually doesn't take very long to do that progession. So that would be for someone just starting out or 

has limited mobility for whatever reason maybe coming back from an injury... you use whatever tools you need at the 

time. For those of us trying to build strength some of us would have the misconception as this is up higher off the 

ground it's actually going to be easier and for some people it will be they'll be able to pull more weight off the ground in 

this position but there's going to be a lot of people too that find they can pull less from this position because when the 

bar is started on the ground where it normally is your legs are much more bent and that allows you to get more leg drive 

off of the floor and then continue that momentum through. So if someone is a good fast puller off the floor and can drive 

hard with their legs they can get through that mid sticking point right around the knee region. Other people if they are 

not particularly fast off the floor or they don't push as hard as they could with their legs, they're going to find when they 

get into that position that they're not as strong through the middle there either so when you pick the bar off the floor like 

this and put it on the blocks and then they try and pull it then their leg drive momentum is basically been taken away so 

instead of having the bar down here and being able to drive it with the legs more, now it's here so your legs are much 

straighter right off the very start. So the lower back and the hips take a lot more of the strain so if someone gets to this 

position and lifts it up on the blocks like this and realizes that they're a lot weaker in this position then that's a weak link 

in their chain they can work on. If they could strengthen up the upper part of the lift and they will get a good carry over 

for pulling off the floor. It might be something worth while giving a try if you're a beginner and you need that extra bit of 

mobility work on that to get yourself down to the floor if you're someone who has been doing deadlifts for awhile and 

maybe come to a little bit of a plateau and you're looking for something to push you through, maybe set it up like this 

and then try the ones where you're pulling from a defict where you're standing on the block see how your strength level 

is there then get the bar up a little bit and see how your strength level is there you might find you're weaker in that 

position then you think. Use all the tools that you can to ge the most out of every lift that you can. I hope that this helps 

you out and I will talk to you soon.

Coach Weiss

Title: b'140kg Bench Fail = Ruined Pull Day | C11.3 W19 Cut'
Description:
b'Got excited. Wanted to Bench that sweet 3PPS again... didn't happen.

Benched with a belt on for the first time the other day, thought I had discovered a new friend in it... nope that friend came back to fuck me up something rotten. Ended up holding the 140kg and overstrained my lower back along with tweaking my hamstring.... was like FUUUUUUUUUUUUUUU

Rested for a bit and went again without the belt, felt much better but still no bueno.

Paused benched. Felt good. 

No rows or anything lower back / ham dependant so did some pull ups and bro curlz. 

Shit session.

Thanks for watching!

Title: b'Powerlifting D14 Dead lift and Bench assist'
Description:
b"Today was unexpectedly rough. Turns out my abs were still tired from Friday and I had trouble transferring force during my dead lifting. Translation; I had no pulling power. Hit some flat dumbbell presses for chest and managed a PR. Then on to some lying leg raises. These are where I realized what had happened during dead lifts. My abs were hurting only 4 reps into a set of six. Since lactic acid build up at this point had about the same probability as a pig hitting the elliptical, it had to be residual soreness. I'm stepping up abs because I ignore them and it hurts my squat. Going to be a bit rough I guess.

Dead lift
165 x 6, 220 x 4, , 275 x 3, 331 x 2, 385 x 2, 441 x 2, 495 x 1, 551 x 0,0 (Not even close), 501 x 0,0 (At this point I was a bit unhappy)

Flat dumbbell press
60 x 6, 70 x 6, 80 x 6, 90 x 6, 100 x 6, 110 x 6

Lying leg raises with hip roll up (These suck more than squatting high rep, but less than the ab wheel)
+15 x 6,6,6"

Title: b'Learn Basic Core Exercise with Pilates'
Description:
b'Learn Basic Core Exercise with Pilates 
http://www.pilatesinnerstrength.com.au/pilates-basic-core-exercise/

It is important to practice basic core exercises to remind the brain how to correctly engage the core. This is a simple exercise so you can focus on the breathing and core activation. If your core isn't working correctly, then you will find you are very unstable on the bolster and you will possibly fall off of it.

It's great for anybody, whether you're a beginner at Pilates or whether you've done Pilates for ten years. It is really ideal to do very basic core exercises just to remind the brain of the correct sequence to activate the core, because it is very intricate to engage the core correctly and often our brains will kind of become a little bit slack at making sure it's switching on correctly.

So a very basic core exercise which is brilliant if you're starting to learn Pilates, this is the real test to see whether your core is correctly engaging, or if you have done Pilates for quite a few years, it's great to do this exercise just once a week just to bring your brain back to basics and focus on the sequence of switching the core on.

So what you're going to do is lay on a bolster, that's it, so you've got your tail bone on the bolster and your head is also supported on the bolster. Neutral spine, feet and knees hip-width apart and hands and arms just nice and relaxed down by your side, not way out to the side, keep them closer towards the hips.

Ok so taking a breath in is to prepare, you're always going to breathe out on the movement. So breath in, breath out, you're going to engage your core on the breath out first and then you're going to float one arm and the opposite leg up towards the ceiling.

So your hand is going be right on top of that shoulder and your knee should be ideally on top of your hip, knee at a right angle position.

Take a breath in to prepare, exhale, you're going to engage your core and float the next leg up. Breath in to hold, breath out to engage your core to float that leg down again. So the same leg that just moved. Breath in to hold, breath out, engage your core and then the opposite arm and leg float back down.

So then you repeat on the opposite side, breath in, breath in, breath in, breath in. So it's a really slow movement, focusing on the breath and what you want to do is always engage your core on the breath our before the movement and keep your core fully engaged throughout the movement.

If your core is not engaged correctly or if it switches off throughout the movement, you'll find you will be very wobbly on the bolster and you might actually even fall off, so do be careful if you are a beginner and you're just learning how to get your core switched on.

So it's very simple, its opposite arm and leg up first on the breath out, inhale to hold, exhale to float the next leg up, inhale to hold, exhale, that same leg floats back down. Inhale to hold, exhale, opposite arm and leg.

So about five repetitions on each side, it's great to do. So it's called "balancing act" because it's all about engaging your core so that you're nice and strong and stable and you keep balanced on the bolster.

Title: b'Effective Tricep Training with Mark Ottobre at Enterprise Fitness Melbourne'
Description:
b"http://www.melbournepersonaltrainers.com 

For effective tricep training, Mark is using a Tom's Combo Bar from Watson Gym Equipment. 

To learn from Mark at one of his Internship or Extended Learning programs visit http://www.melbournepersonaltrainers.com/events/. 

If you would like further information about training with Mark or a member of the Enterprise Fitness team, email info@enterprisefitness.com.au or call 1800 887 143. 

For the latest updates from the studio, subscribe to this YouTube channel and \xe2\x80\x98like\xe2\x80\x99 Enterprise Fitness on Facebook at Facebook.com/EnterpriseFitnessAustralia. 

Download your free eBook \xe2\x80\x98Eat Your Way to Abs\xe2\x80\x99 at the main page of the Enterprise Fitness website (www.melbournepersonaltrainers.com).

Enterprise Fitness is Melbourne\xe2\x80\x99s premier Personal Training studio. Founded by Mark Ottobre, his vision is to create the most professional and education driven personal training company in Australia, as it is education that leads to lasting results.

At Enterprise Fitness, we make your fitness goals a reality and we have the track record and reputation to back it up. Our goal is to make health and fitness apart of your lifestyle.

As we pride ourselves on the highest level of service we do not offer gym memberships or casual passes to our facility. This means that as a client of Enterprise Fitness you will never need to wait for equipment and will be guided step by step through your training, nutrition and supplementation.

However this is just one of the many benefits you will experience training with Enterprise Fitness. At Enterprise Fitness, it is our specialized knowledge that sets us apart. Having trained countless bodybuilders and figure champions, fitness models and fitness competitors we know how to get results in the most effective and efficient time frame possible.

However, please don\xe2\x80\x99t be confused, we don\xe2\x80\x99t only train fitness competitors, we work with a broad spectrum of the population with the one commonality- they\xe2\x80\x99re all serious about making a positive change and getting the results they have always wanted.

With any new client starting with Enterprise Fitness, the first thing to do is to accurately assess your starting point. Maybe your starting at 25-30% body fat and want to lose 10-15 kilos or maybe your starting at 13% body fat and wanting to get just a \xe2\x80\x99little\xe2\x80\x99 leaner and build muscle? Where ever you are right now is perfect and we can help you.

In the first session we discuss your goals, measure your body fat and take your BioSignature. From here we do a structural balance assessment and are able to design you a specific training, nutrition and supplementation protocol to ensure you maximise your results whether the goal is weight loss, strength, to increase muscle, fitness or to get you ready for a comp or photo shoot. Whatever the goal, we got you covered.

Our studio is fully decked out with the highest quality equipment from Elieko, Pendlay, Australian Barbell, Life Fitness, Watsons Custom Strength and Iron Edge. It is a fully equipped private gym with only the best equipment to meet our high standards of practice.

And no, we don\xe2\x80\x99t have treadmills. When you train with us we will rip open a new exciting world of exercise that awaits you. We do not rely on cardio equipment to train our client, instead we show you fun, safe and effective training that actual gets you in shape (and keeps you in shape). I mean seriously, who wants to pay a personal trainer to walk with them on a treadmill?!

We invite you to come and experience the difference of training with bona fide world leaders in the field of fitness.

Make the decision to train with the best personal trainers in Melbourne at our premier personal training studio located on 381 Swan Street, Richmond.

What to do next?

If you would like to book in a time to discuss your goals please give us a call on 1300 887 143 to make an appointment (and no, this appointment won\xe2\x80\x99t cost you a dime.) Just bring yourself and your list of questions.

Alternatively, you can email info@enterprisefitness.com.au with a little about you and why you want to work with Enterprise Fitness."

Title: b'Sample Finisher: Battle Ropes'
Description:
b'Sample Finisher - Battle Ropes (These ones are 2")

Set 1: Alternating Small Waves, Circles, Big Double Slams
Set 2: Small Double Waves, Claps, Big Alternating Waves
Set 3: (SEATED) Alternating Small Waves, Circles, "Big" Double Slams
Set 4: (SEATED) Small Double Waves Side to Side, Claps, Big Alt. Waves
Set 5: Small Alternating Waves, Circles, Big Double Side to Side Slams
Set 6: Small Alternating Waves, Claps, Big Double Slams

Have done up to 10 sets with the 1:1 Work:Rest ratio. Can be done with just one exercise for the entire 30 seconds, or different Work:Rest ratios. Just be creative. Seated ropes are much harder!'

Title: b'Kilimanjaro Training Day A'
Description:
b'Training For Altitude- 

Before Each Floor Exercise - 30 seconds Plank
 5 x Squat Jumps
 20 x (Floor Exercise)
 10 Seconds Rest

Floor Exercises: (1 in each segment only)
Push Ups / Lunges / Crunches / Prone Cobra / Russian Twist

Repeat the process for 3 total circuits.

The Plyometric Force of The Jump Squats keep the heart rate in a higher zone, which cant be maintained for long, thus the rest period.

This conditions the heart and lungs to more effectively process oxygen for metabolic and muscle use. This resembles the need for a more efficient cardiovascular system while at high altitude, due to the lack of oxygen.'

Title: b'Get Fit Over 40 Update Video - 5 Weeks Out Victoria Cup (No Shirt)'
Description:
b"http://www.GetFitOver40.com - Get Fit Over 40 Update Video - 5 Weeks Out Victoria Cup (No Shirt).


Getting a bit closer now, only 5 weeks plus a few days out from my Men's Physique contest at the Victoria Cup. I started last week with my weight cut since I do not have a lot of extra body fat to lose. I really only need to lose about 5-6 pounds of fat, last week I was able to cut out about 5000 calories below maintenance from my diet so that should of equaled around 1.5 pounds of fat loss. I am currently around 190-192 pounds and my Skulpt Aim Muscle Quality Meter as showing about the same body fat percentage as the week before (about 7.5%).

I am not surprised at these results, tech gear is not always 100% accurate so there are going to be slight deviations. What I need to do is stay focuses and trust that my program is going to get me to my body fat percentage goals, over time I will see the results I want!

The lighting in this video was not all that great for showing cuts so you may not notice any improvement over last weeks video update, after all it is only a little over a pound of fat loss so there is not much to see just yet. The big changes will take place in the last 2 weeks as I get really aggressive with my diet at that point :)

Title: b'Burpee push up + squat sandbag - Terry Fitness'
Description:
b"Come si esegue il Burpee push up con squat sandbag, esercizio per allenare i Pettorali, le Braccia, I Glutei, le Gambe e le Spalle

Esecuzione del Burpee push up con squat sandbag:

1. Tieni il palmo della mano completamente sopra il sandbag, effettua un salto indietro con entrambe le gambe fino a raggiungere la posizione di push up

2. Effettua un push up, assumi la posizione di squat con un salto avanti ed eleva con un altro salto il corpo in alto pi\xc3\xb9 che puoi

3. Impugna il sandbag, portalo verso le spalle ed effettua uno squat spingendo pi\xc3\xb9 che puoi indietro e in basso i glutei

4. Riporta a terra il sandbag e impeti dall'inizio.

Errori comuni nel Burpee push up con squat sandbag:

\xe2\x80\xa2 Tenere solo le dita in appoggio invece che tutto il palmo
\xe2\x80\xa2 Sbattere in modo violento le punte dei piedi mentre si effettuano i salti
\xe2\x80\xa2 Avanzare con le ginocchia durate la fase di squat.

FULL Workout Below

1 Leg Legpress 20 Reps each side for 3 sets

Legpress First 8 Really Slow and Controlled hold at bottom and back up. After 8 Reps do 12 Fast Reps and then 3 reps with resistance on it. Do this whole thing for 3 sets - Inspired By Rob Did It

Warm Up Squats

Pyramid Drop Set Squats: 2 Reps Then Drop Weight 6 Reps Drop Weight 12 Reps Drop Weight 20 Reps. So 4 Drops for each set. Do This for 3 Sets of the whole thing

Walking Lunges To Air Squats: Do 5 Walking Lunges To 5 Air Squats. Do this as far as you can for whatever amount of weight you can. If body weight is to easy then put weight above your head

Full Circuit No Stoping
5 Stiff Leg Deadlifts
5 Bent Over Rows
5 Cleans
5 Overhead Pres
5 Squats

Do The above circuit for 5 whole sets of everything

That is the Complete Workout Provided by the Metroflex IX3 Alpha Lady's. Give it a try and let me know how you like it. It took us about 2 hours to finish and that would have been to long for video. "

Title: b'Zhang Gouzheng Profiles'
Description:
b'Many dots means I don't understand what is being said.



"This competition is very important to me. Pressure comes from everywhere but I hope the pressure becomes a form of motivation. I do not want to give myself any way of turning back.. I hope to cut all ways of turning back."

Athen Olympics Weightlifting 69kg category competition, the first lift which is the snatch isn't Zhang Guozheng's stronger lift but he performed great and lifted all 3 attempts.. leaving rival Lee Bae-Young trailing in the dust.

.......

"Why do I say that? Logically, because after the snatch, I was leading by 7.5kg and the Clean and Jerk is my stronger lift and I am the world record holder as well."

"At that point of time, I felt like dying as my waist could't take it already. From the 2nd attempt onwards, (Zhang mentioned an injury which i do not what is it). For the 3rd attempt, when I brought the barbell to here, the whole waist came/popped out. and then (Something about his upper limbs/body not working already)"

"Such a big competition, I couldn't bear to dump the weight. I clenched my teeth and just lifted it overhead. Actually, I knew that even though I could lift it up, I would miss it. However, at that point of time, I hope that somewhere in this despair, I could somehow struggle for it. A heart-breaking kind of pain.. one is the pain from the injury.. one is an inner pain in my heart. It was like giving the chance to someone else. I was carried by two big guys.. both legs were actually empty. I couldn't even touch the floor. After that, I laid down on the floor and our team doctor Liu Zhang Jiang who has been with me for many years, understood it.. he knew what was the condition. Both hands went to work and you could hear the inside, it was brittle/weak.. Immediately, the ice/cold spray(anaesthetic i guess) was used on all over my skin and it felt like tearing/spiltting apart. Something about stopping the blood flow. I just laid there and was really crying in pain. One is the injury pain and one is giving the chance to someone else."

Something about Korean weightlifter Lee Bae-Young......

and Zhang Guozheng laying on the ground, celebrating in his tears, his Olympic Gold medal.

blablabla.....

"I was crying in pain and also crying in joy.. and also crying from emotions within my heart.. all kinds of feelings were trapped inside.. and also crying because I missed my family. You look at me.. in suffering and my waist not being able to take it.. Maybe the people who would understand you the most are still your family."

"Hey wife! Are you happy or not? Wife, I love you to death.. HAHAHA"

A lady commenting: "Your waist is alright already eh?"

Zhang: "Ah, I feel better by 80% just by thinking about wife."

"Actually, they(TV station) were quite wrong/bad, I said many things in front of the camera.. I said many thanks, thanks the party, thanks motherland, thanks our province, thanks our school.. I said many things but they filmed this part only and put it on TV."

Zhang Guozheng always put on the cheerful side of him but in the background, only he himself and his family understand the hardwork and pain. For an Olympic gold medal, many sacrifices might have to be made.. but Zhang Guozheng has no regrets.

"worth it.. worth it.. it's really worth it. Why do I say that? I feel that a person shouldn't just live his life healthily.. it also requires a 'spirit' to live. Should I collapse mentally/spiritually, I feel that it is meaningless to live on anymore. ...... That's why I say it's worth it."

Despite Zhang Guozheng collapsing on the stage from his injury, he still became the champion in this event. In the history of the Olympics, some competitors got injured during competition and continued competing. It wasn't to win medals but to finish the competition.'

Gym-Ken Gymnastics is located at 184 Rockingham Rd in Windham, NH. We host Parkour classes and Open Gyms on Tuesdays and Thursdays with Mr. Jonathan as the teacher...Its Epic!

$15 8:30-10:30 every Thursday night Plus Pizza Prizes!

Parkour is defined on the World Federation of Parkour and Freerunning's (WFPF) Website as one of three possibilities. Moving from point "A" to point be in the most efficient, direct, or creative way possible. At Gym-Ken we let you choose the way you train. 

If you want to use the least amount of energy by getting a ladder and climbing rope to get over the building in your way we support your choice. If you need to boost your strength so you can run up the building grab the top and muscle up and over we can help with the conditioning and give you a place to practice. If you are all about pure flash and want to nail the biggest tricks so you can push your creativity to a whole new level we have the technique and the know how to help you reach your goal. Even if you do Crossfit or boot camps we have what you need to get your movements to the next level.

No only do we have the most talented group of tracers and trickers in the north east, but we also have the most supportive group as well. Come down every Tuesday and/or Thursday night from 8:30-10:30pm and train with the best so you can be your best. **Core Workout - Strong, Tone & Confident:
Start off in a seated position and get comfortable with contracting and releasing lower abdomen in concert with the breath - then add on Kapalabati breathing 20-100 exhalations (no strain, comfortably!)
Level 1: Basic crunch, Basic Oblique Rotation, Locust Pose
*Yoga Push-up: lower to chaturanga, push back up
Level 2 on the Stability ball: Stability Crunch, Stability Oblique Rotation, Stability Locust lift/lower
*PushUps: either on the knees or from plank position
(*as many as you can keep good form, moving down and up as a unit, without sinking into your back)
Level 3 moving into yoga positions with "suspended" pelvis. hold plank pose 30 sec-1+ minutes (try it, you will feel your core!) then move into side plank prep moving side to side from your waist, hold side plank when you are ready for 30 sec-1 minute (listen to your wrists!)

Title: b'Quad Stretch: Avoid This Mistake'
Description:
b'Although performing a quad stretch appears simple, many people actually perform it wrong. The quadriceps are composed of 4 muscles, which include the Vastus Medialis, Vastus Lateralis, Vastus Intermedius and the Rectus Femoris. 

Out of all 4 of the quadricep muscles, the Rectus Femoris is special because it is the only one that has attachments to your pelvis as well. This muscle besides doing knee extension also performs hip flexion.

Many people when stretching their quads either bend forward or keep their thigh forward while doing a standing stretch. This is the wrong way to do a quad stretch because your Rectus Femoris is still on slack. If this muscle becomes tight, it can cause knee pain and back pain from tilting your pelvis forward.

To perform an effective quad stretch, you must stand upright and pull your thigh back so that your knee is pointed straight down towards the ground. Hold that stretch 30 seconds and do it twice on each side.

Title: b'Torphichen and Bathgate Pipe Band - British Championships, 2011'
Description:
b"Torpichen and Bathgate Pipe Band playing in the British Pipe Band Championships held in Annan, Scotland on 25 June 2011. The band is led by Pipe Major Stuart Shedden and Leading Drummer Callum Firth.

The band's medley comprises: Angus MacKenzie of Dumbarton, Ryan's Reason, Last Tango in Harris, Jimmy Ward's Jig, Lily's March, The Smith's a Gallant Fireman, The Old School House, McFadden's Reel, Caithness Reel, and Dancing Feet.

This is, I think, the only UK Grade One pipe band which has not been documented on this channel until now. I was determined last season to rectify this. I recorded the band at Gourock - only to have their performance interrupted by a loudspeaker reminder to head over to the bungy jumping. I also recorded the band at Dunbar - but someone had the great idea of holding the Grade One competition next to a specially customised car which bounced up and down while emitting loud music from a number of speakers. Even here, at Annan, there is more crowd noise than there should be for a major championship."

Title: b'The Iron Spartan 4'
Description:
b'Chris Pluhacek is The Iron Spartan. In this episode of The Iron Spartan, Chris competes in the APF Powerlifting and Bench Press Nationals at the Europa Show of Champions in Orlando. 

Here's what Chris had to say after the meet. "Going into the competition I felt great.\xc2\xa0 It was a lot earlier than most competitions and I am not a morning person by any means, but I felt great.\xc2\xa0 Pounding diet green tea all morning, and hitting the Hemo-Rage Ultra Concentrate before each even helped A TON! Overall I feel I could have done better, but still had higher numbers than in previous meets.\xc2\xa0 
\xc2\xa0
My highest raw squat in a meet was 585 and that was with knee wraps.\xc2\xa0 I hit 595 with just a belt in this meet.\xc2\xa0 Going for 617 on my last attempt, after watching the video, I had my foot placement off from normal, and didn't keep my core tight.\xc2\xa0 

Going into bench, buzzing on Hemo, I felt on top of the world.\xc2\xa0 402 was easy, then for 430 felt even lighter.\xc2\xa0 My breathing was off when I went to 460 and and the pause before the call was real long, at least in my head.\xc2\xa0 I exploded off my chest but just inches to lockout and the bar came to a halt.\xc2\xa0 I think I may have over trained chest going into this.\xc2\xa0 I hit 495\xc2\xa0touch and go a couple weeks earlier.\xc2\xa0 May have forced my body into peaking too early on bench.\xc2\xa0 
\xc2\xa0
Deadlifts, I have no complaints.\xc2\xa0 Easy opening attempt of 600, then 705 felt like a warm up.\xc2\xa0 Jumped to 750, which would be a new personal record and later to find out a new federation record. I got it up and the crowd was ecstatic, then the side judges called hitching.\xc2\xa0 Hitching is if you bounce the bar or lean back and try and guide it up your thighs.\xc2\xa0 I watched the video from different angles, and the call could have gone either way.\xc2\xa0 What was more irritating is watching a guy that the judges knew for a long time do way worse than I did and get all white lights for a good lift!\xc2\xa0 Only thing this means is that I come back for the next one and pull 800!!!\xc2\xa0 No big deal!\xc2\xa0 
\xc2\xa0
Best part was meeting all the people at the booth the day before, and seeing all the faces in the crowd coming to support me in true Team Nutrex Fashion!\xc2\xa0 Couldn't ask for a better family!"

Visit http://www.nutrex.com often to keep up with The Iron Spartan blogs.'

Title: b'Single Slide Squats (How to get Lean Sexy Toned Legs)'
Description:
b'Move of the week: Single Slide Squats

Targets: Glutes (butt), Quads and Inner Thighs

Equipment needed: Towel, Fuzzy Socks or a Furniture Mover Disk

Step 1: 
Start by standing up straight with your feet hip width apart (abs engages, rib cage is lifted, shoulders are back and down away from your ears and looking forward). Shift your balance on your LEFT leg as you squat down on it while your RIGHT leg slides straight out to your side. Still keeping your chest up and looking forward. Arms may be out in front of you for balance or above your head for a more advance move.

Step 2:
Stand back up into starting position by squeezing your LEFT Glute\Quad as well as your RIGHT Inner Thigh to draw your RIGHT leg back to standing position. Exhale during this motion.

Note: Keep you chest lifted and looking forward with your abs engaged throughout the entire move. Really concentrate on the muscles being worked, nice controlled movements.'

2- 2 pull-ups, 8 push-ups (split in 2 sets), 18 curl-ups (split in 3 sets)
3- 3 pull-ups, 12 push-ups (split in 2 sets), 27 curl-ups (split in 3 sets)
4- 4 pull-ups, 16 push-ups (split in 2 sets), 36 curl-ups (split in 3 sets)
5- 5 pull-ups, 20 push-ups (split in 2 sets), 45 curl-ups (split in3 sets)
6- 6 pull-ups, 24 push-ups (split in 2 sets), 54 curl-ups (split in 3 sets)
7- 7 pull-ups, 28 push-ups (split in 2 sets), 63 curl-ups (split in 3 sets)
8- 8 pull-ups, 32 push-ups (split in 2 sets), 72 curl-ups (split in 3 sets)
9- 9 pull-ups, 36 push-ups (split in 2 sets), 81 curl-ups (split in 3 sets)
10- 10 pull-ups, 40 push-ups(split in 2 sets), 90 curl-ups (split in 3 sets)

Now go back down the same way you went up. Don't give up! 

9- 9 pull-ups, 36 push-ups (split in 2 sets), 81 curl-ups (split in 3 sets)

At Home Workout Playlist! - http://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLtlNrUpS714lILyP-eHFDWNwYegwGsGU6 

TRX Atomic Pushup pushups on the ground - suspended pushups - atomic pushup
Swiss Ball 1 arm Row
Swiss Ball Roll Outs
Swiss Ball Low Back Extension

Great work so far on your home workouts! Keep the comments coming and let me know what's working and what you're struggling with. We are going to integrate many different muscles groups into these exercises so we are efficient with our time. Try to get 10 or more reps of each of these 4 exercises, and after you finish, start over and repeat it 2-3 more times if you can. As a reminder, pick the variation of each exercise that matches your ability level. I've got some good stuff for you today so let's get moving!

We are going to start with the TRX Atomic Pushup. Beginners can do pushups on the ground without the TRX, or do plain suspended pushups, but if you are up for it, the Atomic Pushups are AWESOME! It is a great total body exercise using so many muscles. A simple way to get your feet in the straps is to start sitting facing the TRX and put your feet in the straps, and just turn around to a prone position. Perform a pushup, and on the way up, lean over your wrists, draw your abs in and bring your knees toward your chest. Extend back to Pushup Position and repeat. Again, don't arch your back, and try to keep your elbows in toward your body. 

Next we are going to do a single arm row using our ball as a support or bench. Keep your back flat, abs drawn in, and try not to shrug your shoulders. And of course to make it more difficult on this one, just add more weight. We are going for 10 reps on each side and if you can do 15 reps without breaking form, you might want to go for a heavier weight. With your left foot forward, you are going to use your right arm to do the work and the left arm for stability on the ball. Make sure you get both sides in and then we are on to the next exercise!

Which is the Ball Rollout. This is kind of like an ab wheel, but using a ball. The further you extend and the farther out you go, the more difficult it is. Make sure you do not arch your back, keep your abs pulled in and use your abs and lats to pull your body back to the starting position. If 10 is super easy on this exercise, feel free to do more. 

Next, you are going to use a wall to support your feet and put hips on the ball and you are going to do a lower back extension. This is a good exercise for your lumbar spine. If you find it super easy, you can do more reps - even 20 or 30, or add a little weight, but don't over do it! 

Good, Now start over and do all that again and try to get 3 to four sets in. If you still have gas in the tank, you can try another workout in this playlist. In other words, combine these workouts to push yourself further. Which leads me to my question for you today which is How many sets are you getting in? 2, 3, 4? I wanna know how you are doing! Hope you enjoyed todays workout and stay tuned because we have plenty more where that came from. Next week I'll be back in the kitchen with a healthy recipe since it's the last monday of the month so make sure you are subscribed. Also, if you have an Android Phone, you can download the Fitness On The Run app from the Google Play Store which will alert you right away when I upload a new video! Jon Ham from Fitness On The Run, and I'll see you Next Monday!!!

---Estrategia---
Primeape: Es inteligente, usa Doble Equipo para subir su evasion, asi su Pu\xc3\xb1o Certero nunca fallara, usa Avalancha para acabar con los Pokemon Voladores que se cruzan en su camino, es un poco dificil...

Poliwrath: Tiene una tactica tambien: Usa hipnosis para dormir a tus Pokemon y que luego nunca falle su Golpe Certero. Poliwrath no tiene Doble Equipo, por lo que tus golpes talvez no fallen, mientras no estes dormido. Lo que puedes hacer es usar un ataque como Alboroto para que tus Pokemon nunca duerman, asi podras vencerle.

Pu\xc3\xb1o Certero: Este ataque es fuerte, pero es de dos turnos: El primer turno carga, pero si es golpeado primero, no atacara el proximo turno, por lo que el rival no debe atacar para que funcione...

Title: b'Pull Ups Workout For Back'
Description:
b'Pull Ups Workout For Back 
We go over pull ups to isolate certain back muscles. Pull ups aren't just using your arms but engaging the posterior muscles as well as your core area.

Muscles used

Shoulders

The latissimus dorsi and the lower sternal fibers of the pectoralis major are involved in extending/adducting the arm from the overhead position. These muscles do not connect to the scapulae, and their use reduces the need for muscles which attach to them.

The posterior deltoid muscles and teres major muscles are extensor/adductor muscles which attach to the scapulae. The lower trapezius and pectoralis minor are involved as scapular depressors. Pectoralis minor works in conjunction with the levator scapulae muscles and rhomboid muscle to downwardly rotate the scapulae. If one leans back during a pull up, the rhomboids also work with the lower traps to retract/adduct the scapulae.

The serratus anterior pulls forward to rotate the scapula downward and stabilize the shoulder during descent.

Elbow

Muscles which flex the elbow joint are also involved in providing ideal leverage for shoulder extension/adduction. The biceps brachii muscle is involved in dynamic stabilization; it shortens as the elbow flexes yet lengthens as the shoulder extends. It is strongest with a supine grip (what people recently identify with "chin up"). The brachialis and brachioradialis attach to the humerus rather than the scapulae so they only shorten as the pull up is performed. They are relied on even more heavily with a prone grip which limits the biceps' involvement.

Core

The rectus abdominis, erector spinae, the fibers of the transversus abdominis attached to the inguinal ligament[9] and internal obliques/external obliques[8] are used to hold the hips and rib cage together and support the spinal ligaments in resisting the traction of gravity.

Pelvic tilt and the orientation of the legs can alter which of the core muscles are used to bear their weight. If the legs are lifted to the front and the pelvis tilts posterior, the rectus abdominis (with aid from the psoas) bears more weight. If the legs are lifted to the back and pelvis is tilted anterior, the erector spinae (with aid from the lats) bear more weight. Raising the legs and one side of the pelvis laterally will result in more weight born by that side's obliques.'

Title: b'CrossFit Rope Climb Training With CrossFit Cabarrus, LA'
Description:
b"Fix 4 The Day visits CrossFit Cabarrus in Concord, NC and learns how to rope climb. 

F4D website: http://www.fix4theday.com

F4D Facebook: http://www.facebook.com/fix4theday

F4D twitter: https://twitter.com/fix4theday

**********************************************************************
CrossFit Cabarrus opened its doors in December 2011 and is already a success in the Concord, NC area. It has approximately 130 members and 7 coaches on staff and all are eager to learn more about CrossFit.

Fix 4 The Day visited the area's newest box and watched as many members attempted their first ever rope climb. The coaches explained the best techniques for getting up the rope quickly and safely. Rather than use their upper body to pull themselves up the rope, athletes were instructed to wrap the rope over the dominant foot and step on it with the opposite foot, using it much like a brake. The athlete simply brings his knees as high as possible towards his chest, applies the brake, and stands while reaching up the rope with the arms. Using this technique, the athlete gets a firm and safe grip on the rope and uses the lower body for the bulk of the work. Rope climbing is not all about strength, but more about proper technique and footwork to climb efficiently. It also takes practice, but some Cabarrus CrossFitters quickly picked up this skill.

The WOD for this evening consisted of 5 minutes of all out effort at each of the four stations - rowing, slam balls, knees to elbows, and double unders. Good Ass Work, CrossFit Cabarrus! 

CrossFit Cabarrus is located inside the Sports Center facility in Concord, NC. They offer numerous classes throughout the day and surely one fits in your schedule. Good luck, CrossFit Cabarrus, and welcome to the community!"

Title: b'VF Workout 27 - One Arm Clean 32kg'
Description: b"1 Arm Clean with 32kg/70lb Kettlebell. One Switch 3 minutes each hand. Stable set, getting work in, keeps the grip and back working while hands get ready for something serious. You can't work near max every day but if someone suggests a strict Periodization Plan for kettlebells, they just don't know about this type of training or aren't telling you the full story. Yes, it works for lower levels to have simple plan, but even for less intense goals it's good to understand your body. If you can learn something about yourself and start to feel your true status for the day, you begin to get something more than just Fitness or Conditioning from your workouts. Your results are your own. Title: b'2.5-Weeks out of CBBF Junior Nationals 2013(SHOULDERS!)'
Description: b'I am currently 2.5 wks out of competition. Very much on track. Morning weight is at 211 and evening weight is at 216. I hav kept maximal muscle on my diet plan. I had very successful off seoson and so far having a very successful prep. Coming right on track and everything is going as planned, I have worked really hard all yr for this day and looking forward to be on stage and be alot better than I was last yr at nationals when I got 5th. hoping to break into top 3 in Canada in my division, but going for 1st. Want that ultimate results driven challenge? 

Whether beginner or advanced gym user or sports athlete, we have the personal trainer to help you achieve the goals you have set yourself and all at a very reasonable cost.

Nautilus Plus has no joining fees... not now... not ever!

We look forward to seeing you at Nautilus Plus very soon!'

Title: b'Como Aumentar De Masa Muscular Con Un Entrenamiento Perfecto Y Una Dieta Poderosa'
Description:
b'Haz Clic Aqu\xc3\xad: \xc2\xbb\xc2\xbb http://tinyurl.com/GanarMusculatura \xc2\xab\xc2\xab

Uno de los deportes m\xc3\xa1s aconsejados para mantener los brazos en forma es la nataci\xc3\xb3n, porque se puede practicar a cualquier edad, logrando beneficios en la musculatura de hombros, dorsales y pectorales y no causa impacto en las articulaciones.
El tenis es otro de los deportes que son beneficiosos para lograr una buena tonificaci\xc3\xb3n, porque ayuda a quemar calor\xc3\xadas, ejercita hombros y pectorales, las piernas y adem\xc3\xa1s mejora los reflejos y la coordinaci\xc3\xb3n. 
El remo es ideal para trabajar la musculatura de espalda y los brazos, reduce la grasa y puede realizarse en el agua, en el gimnasio o en una m\xc3\xa1quina especial.
El boxeo, realizado en gimnasio y con un punching ball o thai boxing, es un deporte que logra combinar los movimientos de artes marciales con el boxeo, brindar\xc3\xa1 la forma deseada y adem\xc3\xa1s es ideal para descargar tensiones
Lo importante es la constancia: trabajar cinco minutos al d\xc3\xada.'

Title: b'CrossFit - The Warrior Spirit: Part 4 A Warriors Advantage'
Description:
b"On February 12-13, 2008, a CrossFit HQ staff went to Alamo CrossFit in San Antonio, TX for a special Level 1 certification seminar. Members of the Warrior Transition Battalion from the Brooke Army Medical Center gathered to learn the basics of functional movement and how to scale for any starting point.

In this video by CrossFit Again Faster, Kyle Maynard talks about the gains he's seen\xe2\x80\x94both physical and mental\xe2\x80\x94after every CrossFit workout.

At the event, Kyle went head to head against SSG Gabriel Wright in a Fran demo. Gabriel is one of the physical therapists working with the warriors on their recoveries. He had been dabbling with CrossFit workouts, but this was his first Fran. Kyle did modified KB thrusters and ring-ups. It wasn't close.

5min 33sec"

Title: b'KB Cleans for MTB'
Description:
b"Kettlebell Cleans are a great overall exercise for several reason but they have a very valuable application for mountain bikers that most people don't think about. In short, they teach us the general breathing and bracing skills needed to better absorb trail impacts without getting stiff. This helps us stay in control when overshooting a jump to flat or when we can't avoid a rock or other trail obstacle which keeps the tires on the trail and helps us avoid crashes and injuries.

In this video I detail some coaching cues that have proven very helpful for riders in my facility to both perform this exercise better and get more out of it.

You can check out more tips like this, as well as sign up for the FREE 30 Day MTB Skills & Fitness Program at http://www.bikejames.com/"

Title: b'Labrada Stim-Force Chewables | Pre Workout Supplement Review'
Description:
b'It's Pre Workout Supplement review time! Labrada Nutrition Stim-Force Chewables is the subject this time round and it's my first encounter with a pre workout supplement that comes in a chewable form rather than a powdered pre mix to drink. 

So, my Labrada Stim-Force chewables sample came in an assortment of flavours which I wasn't quite sure what was what. One was definitely apple flavour... the others I'm not so sure about... ass flavour I think. 

This product is an energy / focus stimulant and contains no ingredients specifically for promoting "pump" so I just looked at scoring it on that basis alone. However... 

This product did absolutely nothing for me. I've been off stims for a good five days now as well since my last serving of Dexaprine was used earlier this week... so you would think if I was going to feel anything, now would be the time! No extra energy, no focus, tastes like ass... just a worthless product.

So there you go, don't bother with it, waste of money - only thing going for it is it's "chewable" gimmick for ease of use.

Title: b'Meat Worms from the bodybuilder high protein diet less gross version'
Description:
b"Meat Worms from the bodybuilder high protein diet? respond video to 25 year old Bodybuilder colon infected with 'meat worms'. Its medically documented that young men eating diets high in animal protein are at extreme risk of contracting various parasitic worm infestations. In this video we see approx 10lbs of 'meat worm ball' removed from a 25 year old bodybuilders intestinal tract. Species include the infamous pork, beef and fish tapeworms + pin worms.

Some scientists claim the parasitic worms in this bodybuilders colon & instestine actually helped him stay alive vs getting poisoned by excess endotoxin/putracine production from the rotting animal protein in his guts. There is mixed theories out there but everyone agrees that these 'meat worm infestations' THRIVE on an environment that contains LOTS of animal protein in the form of meat, eggs, dairy, whey, fish, chicken etc.

I remember having worms as a kid and the doctor saying 'maybe eat less meat to starve them out'. That really freaked out my Mother at the time. When I went vegan my stomach got flatter so yeah Im sure those meat eating worms got starved out when they couldnt find any rotting animal products in my colon. http://www.cafepress.com/30bana"

Title: b'Sick & Shredded 4 Summer - Overview of the Cut with Intermittent Fasting'
Description:
b"This was meant to be made before I started the cut but time constraints prevented that! Just wanted to give a brief overview of the 20 Week Cut I am doing continuing with my Intermittent Fasting schedule.

Calories are down at 2400kcal and will be decreased, increased or remain the same in two weeks time when I have comparative figures to go off.

As I mentioned in this video below, I will be lifting heavy in the low rep range for 4-5 sets to better retain strength and muscle mass:

http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-BbBJNGxUKg

I will be keeping carbs fairly moderate to high as opposed to crashing them down to nothing, that will be reserved until the later stages. 

I will also be incorporating diet breaks at either the 8 or 10 week mark in order to better keep strength levels up. Jason Blaha of IceCreamFitness does a great walk through of diet breaks on his channel.

Title: b'How to Take a Punch & Prevent Injury - Desensitizing Punching Mechanics & Body Conditioning 2 of 2'
Description:
b'In this video, we show you one method on how to condition your body in a practical manner to take the shock of getting hit. This will develop your nervous system to to be shocked so that you eliminate fear of getting hit at all since you'll know how to "roll with the punches".

The more you do it, the quicker your body will adapt to it. Anything you expose your body to in a consistent basis, your body will adapt to it. You'd be surprised at what the body is capable of adapting to. Think about the most natural act of giving birth. The body adapts and adjusts so that a baby that is much bigger than the orifice that it comes out of, can safely be expelled. So the reason why I brought that up is to point out the fact that if you expose your body to something long enough, your body will perceive that is the norm & it'll adjust & adapt in order to make what was once painful or uncomfortable, not be so. This is because your body does not dislike uncomfortable stimuli. Therefor, it adapts to anything it perceives or that you program as normal way of life. Just keep in mind you are only trying to desensitize your skin, nerves, muscles, ligaments, tendons, capillaries & bones. So start off lightly. If you do it daily, your body will adapt before you know it and without thinking, you'll gradually find ways to adapt to it. Just always stay under the pain threshold until you FEEL confident to strike or get struck harder, little by little. So embrace discomfort but be fair to your body and your body will be fair to you. In other words, dont try to be a hero/warrior like you see in t.v. and go striking things hard or taking punches hard all of a sudden. Build up the familiarity and in due time, you will be unstoppable. Hope this helps.

The tilting of the pelvic helps to preserve energy while keeping your core & midsection activated so that you dont have to waste efforts in tightening up when you're expecting a strike. I learned that through observation of the great Bruce Lee. Notice how he always stood in the "C" shaped-ready stance? Economy of motion my friend.

The twisting is either to "roll with the punches", parry a strike &/or dampen (almost as a counter shot to set a resistance factor so that your opponent reaches fatigue quicker) all done with your midsection. We're only limited to our creativity so if you keep practicing it with an open mind & with an unbiased heart & a neutral warrior spirit your possibilities are endless. Be limitless. Practice your creativity more often (i.e. hand to eye or body part to eye coordination [as in this vid], etc)

You can find the 1st part of this segment here ( http://youtu.be/nr9PJ0ZU_f8 )'

There are many types of stretching exercise in yoga and for the athletes, which require a great flexibility of the body. This requirement can be ultimately fulfilled if the stretching exercises are done with correct stretching techniques. The following are the basic stretches, in yoga and for the athletes:
 
- Dynamic Stretching
- Ballistic Stretching
- Static Active Stretching
- Isometric Stretching
- PNF Stretching

These stretches are required to be done with accurate stretching techniques to get right result. Backbend video here: http://www.yogabodynaturals.com/dropback.html 

Traditional yoga moves are well balanced for every exercise and they demand a complete range of motion, as they perfectly reveal the imbalances. Thus by constructing in symmetrical way, yoga posture allows the intensity of repetition demanded in athletic activity. It helps to prevent injuries that are caused during training exercises these all can be achieved only by correct stretching techniques in yoga. 

Normally athletes get into trouble while training, as they do not know the correct stretching techniques. This type of troubles occurs often due to limited range of motion. Then they use the momentum and rotation of the body to complete a movement that is a bad technique. It can easily result in either injury or strain.

Title: b'How To Make Your Butt In shape'
Description:
b'Visit http://www.thefatlossfactor.asia/ If you really want to loss weight naturally and
fast.I found this website with lots of research on the internet 
about the "how to loss fat". This website will really helps you
to loss your weight

Women want to know what are the best butt exercises to firm and tighten their butt. Many women complain that this is a problem area. That's why I want to share with you the 3 best butt exercises that will slim and sculpt your butt.

Here are the 3 top exercises that every woman needs to know if they want a slim and sexy butt:

1. Squats- This is a great exercise that will help shape your glutes and upper thighs. To perform a squat you would pretend as if you are going to sit down on a chair, with feet shoulder width apart, knees bent, and hold weights at your side. It'Keep your head up and make sure that your back is upright and feet are pointed straight ahead. If your feet are pointed outward it may cause your hips to be tight. The deeper you go, the more you feel your glutes activated. Do anywhere from 8-15 repetitions. Another version of the squat is called a pop squat. This is similar to a squat, using no weight. Simply stay in a squat position with knees bent and jump up and pull your feet together and jump out with feet apart and repeat this movement. Perform 15-30 repetitions. To make this more challenging swing your arms all the way up when you jump up and try jumping up as high as you can off the ground. A few sets of these and you will be seeing your butt looking slim and sexy in no time.

2. Deadlift (single leg)- This exercise will also work on your balance. You may want to use a lighter weight so you can maintain a good balance and increase the weight as you feel more comfortable. Simply stand on one leg and keep your knee bent. The other leg should be off the ground, so that your weight is all on one leg. Bend at your waist and hold a weight on the same side that you are going down on. First, bend at your waist, while you place the weight directly in front of your leg. The idea is to touch the weight to the ground or as close as possible, then come back up and repeat. Perform 8-15 repetitions and switch legs. Performing this exercise one leg at a time you are burning more calories and doing twice the work, which means getting you closer to a slim and sexy butt.

3. Lunges-These are great for shaping the whole leg all the way up to your butt. You can perform what is called a walking lunge with weights or without. If you are doing this with weights, you would hold the weights by your side and walk. Make sure as you walk you are bending your knee and lunging forward. Keep you head up and back straight. Also, make sure that your knee doesn't go over your toe. Count on each leg moving forward about 16-20 steps and back, this is equal to 1 set. There are other ways you can perform a lunge. Another way is to do them in place and alternate between each leg.'

Title: b'My Home Gym self build project pt 32'
Description:
b"Making good progress. Have installed the consumer unit (fuse box), all the light switches and security lights. Got one of the large mirrors in place.

You too can build your own home gym at the bottom of your garden. I was fed-up with exercising in my old, freezing, damp, insect infested garage. So i bit the bullet and decided to get rid of it and have a home gym built in it's place. 

I'm a complete novice in the building game. My achievements or skills before taking on this task - out of sheer desperation - was that i had done the odd bit of DIY in the past, like putting up a shelf, or hanging a picture. All the skills i picked up throughout this journey were mainly thanks to being let down by builders, a little belief, a touch of determination and a shed load of desperation, but most of all, from watching YouTube clips like this journey which I've catalogued. 

Sure i made many mistakes along the way, the build isn't perfect and yeah, if i had my time again there's many things i'd do differently along the way, but my mantra in life which helps me through anything i wish to achieve is to always say to yourself when, not if and you'll find that you can achieve things way beyond yours, or anyone else's expectations. :)"

Title: b'Hit Your Hamstrings, Glutes and Adductors HARD with Big Split DB Stiff-Leg Deadlifts'
Description:
b'The Stiff-Legged Deadlift is a key exercise for hamstring development but it doesn't fully address adductor development.

-----
Get more leg exercises like this at 
http://www.thebestlegexercises.com
-----

Adductor work is where this exercise comes in...it's going to target the adductors with a wide "split" position as you're doing a dumbbell Stiff-Legged Deadlift type of movement. In addition, this will hit the glutes strongly as well.

You can get into position either of two ways. 

First, you can set the dumbbells down beside your lead leg, then reach forward and pick them up and get into the start position, or you can pick up the dumbbells in a normal deadlift, then go from the standing position and step forward into the wide split position.

Either way is fine...pick whichever feels best to you.

To do this exercise, you're going to get into the wide split and STAY there for the entire exercise. Essentially, this is like a very big lunge position.

Keep your legs locked in that position then lean forward in a sort of stiff-legged deadlift type of movement, keeping your lower back arched and your core tight. Don't lean forward so far that your lower back rounds over but do lean as far forward as you can.

Hold for a few seconds in this forward position, then use power from your front leg to pull your torso back to the vertical position. This power should come from your hamstrings and glutes.

Perform your reps on one side then take a rest before switching to the other side. The reason for this is that both legs will be worked to some degree by holding the split. If you go right into the other leg immediately, you won't be able to achieve the same level of workload.

Again, lean forward, keeping your lower back arched.

Come back up to the vertical position and repeat.

The adductors will be worked very strongly in an isometric fashion by holding your body and legs in this wide split position under load.'

Title: b'Home Chest Workouts - Get A Killer Back Workout'
Description:
b'Six pack shortcut exposed: 
http://howgainmuscle.org/go/Sixpackshortcuts 

In this video I show you a quick home workout you can do for chest and back. This is a great workout to get started with at home if you don't have a gym membership. And I will sometimes do this workout when I don't have time to go to the gym, or when I'm traveling and don't have gym access.

Here's the workout:

SIDE TO SIDE PUSHUPS -- 10 REPS. Move your hands wide apart as you go down, and close together when you reach the top of the pushup. Alternate sides, so that you are traveling side to side as you do your pushups.

DUMBBELL FLYS -- 10 REPS. Move the dumbbells up and down in a CIRCULAR motion, not a PRESSING motion like a bench pres. Keep your arms slightly bent. Isolate your chest as much as possible -- you should feel your chest muscles squeezing together as you do this, and minimal tricep involvement.

BENT ARM SIDE LATERAL -- 10 REPS. Keep your arms bent at a 90 degree angle. Raise your arms upwards and to the side. You should feel this in your deltoid (shoulder) muscles primarily. If you are advanced, do this explosively like I do in the video. If you're a beginner, use slower, more strict form and isolate your shoulders more. Be careful with too much back involvement if you're first starting off (it may lead to injury if you're not conditioned to explosive weight lifting moves).

BENT OVER SIDE LATERAL -- 10 REPS. Bend over at a 90 degree angle, so that your back is flat like a table top. You should feel a stretch in your hamstrings as you do this. In this position, contract the muscles of your back to bring the dumbbells upwards in a circular motion. Really contract your back as much as possible at the top of the repetition to get the most out of it. Again, use more strict, slow form than I do in this video if you are a beginner -- use more explosive form if you are advanced.

DUMBBELL FRONT RAISES TO CEILING -- 10 REPS. Keeping your arms bent VERY slightly (almost straight), raise the dumbbells from your legs to vertically above your head. Once again, use strict form if you are a beginner and do not initiate the movement with momentum from your back. If you are advanced, explode from the bottom with a small amount of back involvement, and use a heavier weight.

DUMBBELL GOOD MORNINGS -- 10 REPS. Hold the dumbell to your chest. Bend over from your hips, being careful not to round your back excessively. Go down until you feel a stretch in your hamstring, then keeping your back straight return to the standing position.

And that's it! You can do this once for a quick workout, or 3x for a more thorough workout.

LEAVE ME A COMMENT below to let me know how you liked this workout! And be sure to SUBSCRIBE to ensure you always get the latest videos we post here.

Thanks guys, and I will talk to you in the comments to answer any questions!

And if you want to take the fast track to getting a ripped body and abs, I recommend checking out the "Afterburn Training" video on my site. It shows you my breakthrough training technique that I use to build muscle while staying very lean, and eating tons of food.

Title: b'Counter Balancing your Body with the Pilates Swan'
Description:
b'http://www.lifestylebylindsey.com/

In this video I go over the Swan - The Swan (with the neck roll) is a super cool Pilates Exercise! It counter stretches the spine. When we do a lot of forward stretching exercises, we can actually bunch up the muscles of the spine. This exercise stretches those muscles the other way... Counter-stretching... get it? And it can even help relieve sore back muscles!

Swan is an extension exercise. It is one of the best exercises you can do as a counter stretch for the many forward flexion exercises in Pilates mat work. Swan opens the front-body, expands the chest and stretches the abdominals, hip flexors and quadriceps. Swan also strengthens. Throughout swan, the abdominals stay engaged and the shoulders, back, inner thighs, pelvic floor, glutes and hamstrings are at work.

Swan opens the front-body, expands the chest and stretches the abdominals, hip flexors and quadriceps.

Swan also strengthens. Throughout swan, the abdominals stay engaged and the shoulders, back, inner thighs, pelvic floor, glutes and hamstrings are at work. 

Benefits:

 * Stretches the muscles of the throat and abs.
 * Works the shoulder stabilizer muscles.
 * "Releases" and counterstretches the spine after all the flexing you've done. As such, it is the Pilates alternative to the "Mckenzie Extension exercise" that is famous for relieving sore backs.

http://www.lifestylebylindsey.com/

*This exercise is an amazing choice for improve your Triceps providing a massive appearance of your arms. Today is used in Gyms and sports.

**Check out the following step by step:

00:15 - Material - An adjustable Dumbbell.

00:24 - Positioning - Flex your Knees and contract your Abs for the good equilibrium.
Note: Keep your Torso straight.

00:30 - Execution - Move up the weight and do an extension/flexion of your Elbow.
Note: Keep fixed your shoulder and move only your Elbow. Max contraction of the Triceps muscle.

01:15 - Common error - 1) You have to keep fixed your Shoulder to increase the Triceps work.
2) Be careful to not hit the weight on your Head when you take down the weight.

You can do 4x08-12 reps for better results.

Title: b'My Review of Resistance Bands, Hexagon Dumbbells, and PowerBlocks Classic 50 Plus Set'
Description:
b'Check out my website: http://teamtearitup.com
I can coach YOU to the body you've always wanted! Follow the link and click on "Make Nick My Coach" to start TODAY! http://teamtearitup.com/join-our-team/

When working out at home with a program that includes resistance, it's important to find an option for lifting that works best for your work out space, for your goals, and for your resources. I originally started P90X using dumbbells and my wife started by using resistance bands. These both were great to start with, but they also come with some disadvantages. 

After starting Body Beast, I invested in the classic 50 lb. unit of all-in-one PowerBlocks. After doing a lot of research, I settled on buying these rather than other popular all-in-one units. I know that many people love using Select Tech Dumbbells or Iron Master dumbbells, which are also worth taking a look at. Since I don't own these for now, I don't review them, but the main point here is that All-in-One dumbbells offer a unique and highly efficient way to work out from home. They're great with programs like Power 90, P90X, P90X2, P90X3, Body Beast, Chalean Extreme, Insanity: The Asylum, and many others.

After using all 3 options I review in this video, I prefer all-in-ones to build muscle from home. On the road, I still use resistance bands since they're so portable and take up so little space, but in my regular day-to-day routine, I prefer PowerBlocks (all-in-one dumbbells) over resistance bands and hexagon dumbbells. 

I hope this video gives you some helpful and useful information in your own fitness journey!

b'Natural Bodybuilding "A Battle of Mind"...there is a battle within your mind as you are trying to perform your movements. Your body wants to quit. However, your mind is telling you body NO! That is what must be happening within your mind as you are training. Your mind must win this battle. Your mind controls your body and it is your mind that will allow your body to push beyond its limits and grow. You must conquer your body with your mind. In this video you see a typical superset that Vince and I perform while training arms. The first exercise you see is barbell curls. This targets the biceps and is the main mass builder for the biceps. The second exercise is a variation of a skull crusher. It is performed on a straight bar and applies great emphasis on the triceps. Both of these exercises can be used in conjunction with one another to develop fantastic completely developed arms 100% naturally. Remember, natural bodybuilding is about breakthroughs. You must continue to get stronger in order to demand your muscles to grow.

Title: b'03/10/12 - Por 39\xe2\x82\xac la Piscina de La Nuc\xc3\xada ofrece Gimnasio, Nataci\xc3\xb3n, Spa y 108 clases.'
Description:
b'Para este curso 2012/2013 La Piscina Climatizada Municipal Camilo Cano ofrece a sus usuarios desde 39 \xe2\x82\xac al mes nataci\xc3\xb3n, gimnasio, zona SPA y 108 clases colectivas semanales. Desde el Ayuntamiento y la empresa gestora de la Piscina Municipal Ante la delicada situaci\xc3\xb3n econ\xc3\xb3mica se ha realizado un esfuerzo de descuentos y bonificaciones, as\xc3\xad como mejoras en todas las instalaciones como la ampliaci\xc3\xb3n de la zona de SPA o la renovaci\xc3\xb3n de todas las bicis de spinning.
 La Piscina Climatizada Municipal de La Nuc\xc3\xada es la \xc3\xbanica de la comarca de la Marina Baixa que ofrece por el mismo precio uso libre de la piscina, un completo gimnasio de 350 m2, completa zona termal SPA (sauna, ba\xc3\xb1o turco...) y 108 clases colectivas (TRX entrenamiento en suspensi\xc3\xb3n, spining, pilates, taichi, aquagym, zumba, step, energy box, pole dance, walker....). El horario de la Piscina de La Nuc\xc3\xada es de lunes a viernes de 7 a 22,30 horas, s\xc3\xa1bados de 9 a 21 horas y domingos y festivos de 9 a 14 horas.

Descuentos a parados y jubilados
 La Piscina Climatizada Municipal Camilo Cano de La Nuc\xc3\xada cuenta con descuentos para diferentes colectivos como el 25% a desempleados, 15% a jubilados y 40% a discapacitados. Gracias al convenio con la concejal\xc3\xada de la Mujer, todas las mujeres nucieras tienen un descuento del 50% en la matr\xc3\xadcula para fomentar el deporte femenino.

Servicio de Guarder\xc3\xada y descuentos padre cursillista
Esta semana han comenzado las clases de nataci\xc3\xb3n del curso 2012-2013 con la novedad del servicio de guarder\xc3\xada, donde los padres y madres que realicen deporte en la Piscina Climatizada y en la Ciutat Esportiva podr\xc3\xa1n dejar a sus hijos con una monitora por tan s\xc3\xb3lo 1 \xe2\x82\xac/ hora, a partir de 3 a\xc3\xb1os.
Por otro lado los padres y madres de ni\xc3\xb1os cursillistas tendr\xc3\xa1n una rebaja del 60% en la entrada de un d\xc3\xada a la Piscina. Por tan s\xc3\xb3lo 2,5 \xe2\x82\xac al d\xc3\xada podr\xc3\xa1n practicar deporte mientras sus hijos aprenden o perfeccionan su estilo en nataci\xc3\xb3n.

Matr\xc3\xadcula abierta todav\xc3\xada cursos de nataci\xc3\xb3n
Esta semana se han iniciado los Cursos de Nataci\xc3\xb3n de la Piscina Climatizada Municipal Camilo Cano de La Nuc\xc3\xada, para todas las edades desde los 6 meses hasta 70 a\xc3\xb1os. La matr\xc3\xadcula contin\xc3\xbaa abierta con multitud de horarios y niveles para todas las edades incluso el fin de semana.
Para m\xc3\xa1s informaci\xc3\xb3n, matr\xc3\xadcula dirigirse al Piscina Climatizada Municipal o en el 966895106 o en www.piscinanucia.com.'
