Title: b'Help...Squats Leave Me Out of Breath'
Description:
b"Huge Gainer, the ultimate mass gainer: http://bit.ly/HugeGainer

Massive Iron e-book... http://massiveiron.com

If barbell squats leave you out of breath no amount of volume work in the weight room will really change this much. Your best option is to spend some time doing conditioning work; something that raises your heart rate.

I recommend 3-4 sessions per week of 20 minutes each. It may take 2-4 months to notice a difference, but you will notice a difference.

I suggest avoiding knee-punishing forms of cardio such as running, unless you are in your 20s and aren't overweight.

Need help? Ask me questions here... http://bit.ly/SteveShaw

Title: b'Barres de prot\xc3\xa9ines Crisp-Pro de Kinetica, test et avis sur ces barres prot\xc3\xa9in\xc3\xa9es - musculation'
Description:
b"A voir sur : http://www.guide-proteines.org/proteines-whey/barres-proteines/crisp-pro-kinetica.html

========================

Ces barres de prot\xc3\xa9ines contiennent 10 g de prot\xc3\xa9ines par barre (chaque barre pesant 40 g ). Ensuite il y a presque 14 g de glucides et 9 g de lipides. Il y a donc plus de glucides que de prot\xc3\xa9ines.

On en conclut donc que c'est un compl\xc3\xa9ment alimentaire que l'on va plut\xc3\xb4t utiliser lors d'une prise de masse pour faire une collation. Il ne pourra pas remplacer un shaker de pures prot\xc3\xa9ines.

Le go\xc3\xbbt est bon, \xc3\xa7a ressemble \xc3\xa0 n'importe quelle barre de c\xc3\xa9r\xc3\xa9ales.

========================

Des conseils chaque semaine, abonnez-vous : http://www.youtube.com/user/allmusculation
Suivez nous sur facebook : https://www.facebook.com/pages/All-Musculation/183160313705
Et sur Twitter : https://twitter.com/AllMusculation"

Title: b'How to be INSTANTLY 10% stronger in the One-Arm Dumbbell Row'
Description:
b"http://www.thebestbackexercises.com

So...if there was a way to be 10% stronger in an exercise INSTANTLY....would you use it? Of course you would!

And there IS...

The technique is called Contralateral Antagonistic Muscle Activation. 

The name is long and sounds a bit technical, however, once you understand it, it's really pretty simple.

The key concept is this...by activating the antagonistic muscle on the opposite side of the body as the muscle being worked, you can see an INSTANT 10% increase in strength in the working target muscle. 

The physiological mechanism (if you're interested) is that approximately 10% of the neural fibers that cross over at the medulla oblongata (the connection between the two halves of your brain) reciprocally innervate agonist and contralateral antagonist muscles.

In English, that means that some of the nerves that activate muscle fibers in your left tricep also activate some fibers in your right bicep, and vice versa.

The practical upshot of this is that when you work your right bicep and your left tricep simultaneously, both will see about a 10% instant increase in strength due to increased nervous system activation and fiber recruitment.

Sound interesting? 

I thought so...

The trick is finding exercises that can be done simultaneously in an effective manner.

And that's where THIS exercise comes into play.

You're going to be performing a standard One Arm Dumbbell Row exercise...and at the same time, your support arm is going to be pushing a heavy high-pulley load down onto the bench.

Now, in the original theory behind this contralateral technique, it was advised to use the same tempo for both exercises. In this case, however, you're just going to be doing an isometric contraction for chest activation. I found it to be just as effective in my testing of the exercise.

I HAVE used a simultaneous push/pull for this style of training and, while VERY effective, I actually found I was limited in the amount of weight I could use by the torque my core was capable of withstanding during the paired exercises. I use it as a core exercise regularly but you just plain can't use as much weight due to that issue.

To perform this exercise, you'll need a bench, a dumbbell and a high pulley with a single handle. If you don't have a pulley, you can also use a thick band (or several thinner bands, if that's what you've got). The concept is the same.

Set the bench so that the end is right underneath the high pulley. Set a moderately heavy weight on the pulley and set a dumbbell you could get about 10 to 12 reps with for the row beside the bench.

Get your knee in position on the bench then grab the cable handle with both hands.

Use a powerful downward push with your entire upper body to push the handle down towards the bench. How hard you have to push will depend on how much weight you have on the pulley.

Set your fist on the bench then quickly reach down and grab the dumbbell. Once you pick up the dumbbell, that will counterbalance the pull of the pulley weight and you'll be locked in. Your chest will be in a steady isometric contraction.

Get into position for the dumbbell row. You should have your plant leg out to the side at an angle, knee bent, with an arch in your lower back for support. Look slightly forward to keep a curvature in your neck..this will help you maintain the arch in your lower back.

Now simply row up. Your plant arm/cable arm DOES NOT MOVE. It stays on the bench, right where it is.

As you row up, try to consciously push down into the bench with your support arm to maximize pec contraction. You will also get MASSIVE cross-tension in through your core while performing this technique, so be sure to keep your core tight.

Get as many reps as you can then set the dumbbell down. Grip the cable handle with both hands and bring it back up, setting the stack down (don't let the handle just fly up and the stack crash down).

Then repeat on the other side with the exact same execution.

This technique is demanding but VERY effective. I immediately felt stronger in the exercise the first time I used it.

Once you've tried it out for moderate to higher reps, try it with heavy weight and low reps as well (if you feel comfortable doing so).

In the next set, I'm using a 135 lb dumbbell (125lbs + 10 lbs of Plate Mates magnetic plates attached) and the entire weight stack of cable machine.

The heavier weight requires a BIG push to get the cable handle down into position.

That's the exercise!

It's a very simple setup and the concept is extremely effective.

Give this one a try next time you hit your back. You'll feel a little stronger from the very first rep you do and bottom line...more strength and more weight means more MASS (plus the core work is a nice bonus on the side!)."

Title: b'Workout with Baby in sling'
Description: b'Im a certified personal trainer. I just recently had a baby who is now 7weeks. I could not workout since I was glued to the rocking chair always feeding him. Title: b'Challenges Within (Barthel Fitness Step 2)'
Description:
b'Challenges Within is my video for the Barthel Fitness Sponsorship Contest Step 2. Having to creat a video displaying mentally and physically challenging myself, I thought of challenges I have faced. We all have our doubters, haters, and disbelievers. We all have that side of ourselves that can be discouraged and hurt by what they say. And then we all have that side of ourselves that motivates us, and challenges us to overcome what others say. And to never doubt ourselves. 


Everything said in the video is true. I hold these comments and doubts from others in my mind and remember them clearly. From years ago till now. This is only a few of what has been said. But I wanted to display that no matter what, I have my eye set on a goal and a dream, and if someone doubts me, it does not matter what they say, even though sometimes it gets challenging ignoring them. 

But we all face these mental challenges, and we all have this mental strength. And we can use this to fuel our minds and determination to physically challenge ourselves. 

I want to be a filmmaker.

I love bodybuilding and want to look like a bodybuilder.

I can do these things.

And you can do whatever you have your mind set to.'

Title: b'Kevin Mattson ~ INFINITE POSSIBILITIES'
Description:
b"You cannot discover new oceans unless you have the courage to lose sight of the shore. 
http://forum.bodybuilding.com/showthread.php?t=137405463&page=1
We are all Inventors, each sailing out on a voyage of discovery, guided each by a private chart, of which there is no duplicate. The world is all gates, all opportunities.

***ENERGY*** ***POWER*** ***PASSION***

The Future holds INFINITE Possibilities. The ones that really matter are the ones you choose to follow and bring into reality.
It's Choice... Not Chance... That Determines Your Destiny.

Your time is limited, so don't waste it living someone Else's life. Don't be trapped by dogma - which is living with the results of other people's thinking. Don't let the noise of others opinions drown out your own inner voice. And most Important, have the courage to follow your heart and intuition. They somehow already know what you truly want to become. Everything else is secondary.

It has Always been my Philosophy of Life that Difficulties Vanish when Faced Boldly.

***DEDICATION***DETERMINATION***DISCIPLINE***"

Title: b'Rectus femorus stretch upgrades + Double day training with Pat Lane from Sydney Roosters'
Description:
b"Please LIKE / SHARE if you'd like to see more videos
PROBLEM - Hip flexor tightness is one of the most common movement dysfunctions. It has become so common because we spend so much time seated, driving to work, eating, studying.. and then we squat. 

Squats are great for lengthening the tissues around the back of the hips and the lower back but they require you to create high levels of tension in a shortened position. The same shortened position that we're already spending too much time in.

SYMPTOMS - Knee tendon, or retro-patella pain, anterior hip impingement, inefficient gait - hamstring tears, under-active gluteus, achilles tendon troubles, lower back pain, excessive lumbar lordosis, excessive thoracic lordosis and many other common complaints.

SOLUTION - Create tension a lengthened position for the quadriceps and hip flexors. Aggressive loaded stretches, long duration static holds and dynamic movements like split squats and lunges.

The video explains how to get the most out of the kneeling rec-fem stretch and also my training with Patrick Lane"

Title: b'95% bodyweight bench press for reps and 3.1 mile jog (Pump and Run contest 2013 local gym)'
Description:
b'Pump and Run contest:

Rules:

In this type of contest you perform a bench press for reps with a certain percentage of your bodyweight and then you perform a 3.1 mile run on the treadmill. Each rep you get subtracts 3 seconds off your time, you are allowed to do a maximum of 30 reps, once you hit 31 or more those reps no longer count toward subtracting 3 seconds off your 3.1 mile time. For men age 18-30 they must perform 95% of there bodyweight, age 30-45 perform 90%, 45 and over 85%. For the bench press the rules are upper back, butt, head, and heels must remain flat on the bench and the ground. When doing the reps you must fully lock them out, and no bouncing is allowed while performing them, and finally you can rest up to 3 seconds at the top of each rep. For the 3.1 mile jog on the treadmill, you jog or walk on it until the distance says 3.10. You can adjust the speed or incline to whatever you want during the run. The final score is your 3.1 mile time, and for each rep you did on the bench you subtract 3 seconds off your 3 mile time. So if you did a 30 minute 3.1 mile and 20 reps on the bench your final time is 29 minutes.

I trained for about 4-6 weeks for this.

In the beginning for the bench press I started at 165 x 23 reps and a 33 minute 3.1 jog. 

For the bench my program I came up with I tried to hit the weights I thought I would do contest day for about 25 reps then I would increase the weight by 5 pounds, once I hit 170 x 25 I added 5 pounds each session and maxed out as many reps as possible, some of the numbers I hit were 175 x 23, 180 x 22, 185 x 22, and 195 x 20.8 reps. I did this once a week in the beginning, then twice a week in the mid training, then 3 times a week in the final weeks. 

Increasing the weight worked to my advantage as when I did 170 that day it felt extremely light, my goal was 25+ reps and made sure I could do it with 165 and 170 which is 95% of my bodyweight, as my bodyweight tends to fluctuate between 174.6-181 pounds on a light day and a heavy day. I think by increasing the weight it made my endurance better and my strength.

As for the 3.1 mile jog, I came up with a program where I would increase the speed by about .2 every 2 minutes and start off at a slow speed in the beginning, once I got closer to about the 2.5 mile mark I would start increasing the speed much quicker by .2 - .5 every 20-30 seconds eventually working up to almost a sprint at the end for a short duration. My first day I started at 4.0 and ended at 7.5 speed. 

Each session I would raise my starting speed by about .2 - .5, so the next session I would start at 4.5 and ended at around 8.0. Next session 5.0 - 9.0, 5.2 to 9.5, 5.5 - 10.0, 5.8 - 10.0 where I hit a 26:15. In the contest I started at 6.0 and and once I was around 20 minutes I raised the speed every 30 seconds by 2. - .3 at the 22 minute mark I raised it every 20 seconds, I eventually worked up to 11.0 when I was around 23:40 minutes, and left the speed there. Over the short time I trained, a total of 8 sessions on the jog, I decreased my time by about 8 minutes.'

Title: b'Bodyweight Workouts with TT Europe Workout A'
Description:
b"http://www.turbulencetraining.com 
Visit Turbulence Training to get your FREE sample fat burning workout. 

Here in Paris, we are filming workout A of the TT Europe Vacation program and we are going to start the first superset with a pairing of a hard single leg exercise the Bulgarian split squat with a hard pushup exercise the decline pushup.

For the Bulgarian split squat, do all repetitions for one leg, and then switch over to the other leg, repeating for up to 20 repetitions per side. If you are using dumbbells, then just do 8 repetitions and increase the weight. For beginners, you can start with a regular split squat. 

Immediately moving into the decline pushups, place your feet on a bench and your hands on the ground and perform 20-25 repetitions. For beginners, start with kneeling pushups or regular pushups.

After all the repetitions are completed for the pushups, then rest 1 minute and repeat the superset 2 more times for a total of 3 supersets.

In superset #2 from workout A, you can either do step ups or box jumps, paired with spiderman pushups or whichever pushup you can do with a close-grip. 

The box steps are new to the program, so if you are a beginner, then just start out with the step ups. A box jump simply means you are jumping up onto a level, and it's actually easier on your legs because you aren't going to be coming all the way down so there isn't as much force when you land. 

For the spiderman pushups, start in a pushup position, go down and bring your knee up to your elbow, and then bring it back out, alternating sides. For the close-grip pushup, tuck your elbows into your sides and perform a pushup. 

Now on to the third superset of workout A where you will start with a single leg deadlift and pair that with a pulling exercise (pull ups, chin ups, bodyweight rows, DB rows) for the upper back. 

For the deadlift, do all repetitions for one side and then switch over to the other side.

Once you've completed the strength training portion of Workout A, move into the interval training portion of the workout.

Title: b'Motivational Fitness Transformation: RuneScape Addict to Iron Addict (Part 1)'
Description:
b"I was in the gym for about a year but had very little knowledge on training and nutrition, I got back into Runescape around summer 2014 because of legacy combat... Biggest mistake of my life, a game i vowed to quit, i ended up returning to and getting 3 99's in a span of 5 weeks. Disregarded training and diet, I went from 160 of some gains to 184 of totally fat.. I realized I fell off the thing I had a passion for. Fortunately, right around those realizations I got hacked on runescape! Perfect chance to start over with my fitness journey, i met new friends at the gym who i've seen before but never spoken to and they've helped guide me through what i've accomplished so far. I cut about 34 pounds in 3-4 months, and have 20 more to go. My goals are just to cut down to where i am lean and i can just lean bulk. I really want to thank Gabe & Gian for helping me and motivating me. As well as my friends outside of the gym who help encourage me in some way. Hopefully i wont have a desire to return to runescape. I doubt i will though. I've gone half a year now without it. 

follow me on Tumblr & Instagram! Send me questions on Tumblr!

Title: b'The Iron Edge Dip Belt'
Description:
b"Visit Iron Edge http://www.ironedge.com.au
The Dip Belt

For general strength and conditioning, bodyweight exercises can't be beaten.
They develop not only strength in the primary muscles doing the work, but engage all manner of secondary and stabilizer muscles to give you a holistic benefit you just won't get from a machine or bench-bound exercise.

But eventually, you have to ask the question: what happens when bodyweight isn't enough?

If you ask us, getting a dip belt (or a weighted vest) from Iron Edge is the answer. This way, you can easily -and safely -- supplement your bodyweight with extra poundage.

The Iron Edge Dip Belt is made from nylon and then fitted with neoprene padding to provide comfort and a secure fit. The poundage is suspended from a chain at the front of the belt, which is easily and reliably adjusted by way of a carabiner for easy loading.

For more info ... http://www.ironedge.com.au/store/product.php?productid=1680&cat=0&page=1"

Title: b'Auckland Personal Trainer Squats (140kg x 4)'
Description:
b"Filmed 27th January, 2013. I was going through over-training sickness when these two scenes were filmed. Why? Because I was trying to do too much contrasting workouts - was trying to do 2 - 3 kick boxing sessions p / wk as well. Didn't work out that well for me.

Slow motion to clearly see whether I go below parallel or not. 

As for the single Leg Romanian Deadlifts - 

Many instructional videos on the net have you place the dumbbell under your chest, they are wrong, place it at the base of support -- the foot. 

Hip hinge by shoving hips back along with your rear leg to counterbalance and distribute bodyweight. 

Do not 
--Travel knees forward - this is a hip hinge exercise not a squat. 

- Check yourself out in mirror like I am - tuck chin in to keep balanced and a neutral spine.

- Bend lower back or go below parallel at the expense of lower back bending.

- Knock the exercise off as useless, takes couple weeks to get hang of balance and learn hip hinge before being able to add significant weight 

Bonus tips - 
1) You can use heavier dumbbells with straps -- my grip was starting to fail 

2) If you put chalk on your butt as you can see I did, then, it increases the effectiveness of the exercise.

Good article here - http://70sbig.com/blog/2011/06/the-rdl/

Title: b'Nate Quinn Road to Nationals: Part 3 several weeks after major surgery 2011'
Description: b"This is me trying to come back after surgery September 2011. They had taken out a football size tumor off my liver. Had to take it pretty easy so my guts didn't blast out through my incision but gotta start somewhere. I had to train pretty high rep high volume for awhile. I used a stop watch and took about 30 second rest in between sets to keep intensity there. Most of the time I actually did workouts where I did 3 huge giant sets of 6-10 exercises in a row depending on the body part. Alot of that stuff in the video was recorded during those. For example that leg workout in the video I went from leg ext to leg press to lunges to front squats to leg press to hack squats all in one set. It was the only way I could keep my muscles full with what muscle I had left. I was down alot of weight in all of the 2011 videos."

Title: b'Ejercicios Para Aumento de Masa Muscular - super dieta para ganar peso.'
Description:
b'Haz Clic Aqu\xc3\xad: \xc2\xbb\xc2\xbb http://tinyurl.com/GanarMusculatura \xc2\xab\xc2\xab

1 Predicador con barra.
Sentado en el banco Scott o banco para predicador, sost\xc3\xa9n una barra con pesas y luego flexiona los brazos a nivel de ambos codos, posteriormente regresa la barra a su posici\xc3\xb3n original pero sin dejarla caer de golpe. 

2. Curl concentraci\xc3\xb3n con mancuerna.
Sentado, se sostiene una mancuerna de forma vertical, apoyando el brazo en el muslo a la altura del codo. Se flexionar\xc3\xa1 el brazo hasta levantar el peso y luego descenderemos 
de forma controlada hasta llegar a la posici\xc3\xb3n inicial. Recuerda que el movimiento es \xc3\xbanicamente del brazo y no deber\xc3\xa1s ayudarte por medio del balanceo del cuerpo. 

3. Curl en martillo.
Sentado, con una mancuerna en cada brazo, se flexiona un brazo mientras el otro se extiende de forma alterna. La mancuerna deber\xc3\xa1 ser sostenida en forma de martillo, con lo cual se lograr\xc3\xa1 entrenar de manera mas intensa la regi\xc3\xb3n lateral del b\xc3\xadceps. La espalda deber\xc3\xa1 estar recta en todo momento.

4. Curl con barra.
De pie, con las piernas separadas a la anchura de los hombros, sost\xc3\xa9n una barra con pesas con el agarre hacia adelante. Flexiona los brazos haciendo subir la barra hasta el pecho y luego inicia el movimiento de descenso controlado a la posici\xc3\xb3n original.
Debes mantener tu postura recta durante todo el ejercicio.

5. Predicador con mancuerna.
Sentado en el banco para predicador o banco scott, se sostiene una mancuerna con la mano en l\xc3\xadnea recta con respecto al antebrazo, luego extender el brazo bajando la
mancuerna hasta tocar la almohadilla del predicador, inmediatamente despu\xc3\xa9s y como si dicha almohadilla "quemara", se flexiona el brazo para regresarlo a su posici\xc3\xb3n inicial. Despu\xc3\xa9s de terminar las repeticiones en un brazo, se continuar\xc3\xa1 con el otro.'

Title: b'6 Pack Abs -- Cardio Exercise For 6 Pack Abs'
Description:
b"http://biz48.com/6-Pack-Abs/ Many people out there seem to think that doing countless sit-up and crunches all day will result in toned 6 pack abs. This is a great misconception and nothing could be further from the truth. The truth is that everyone, no matter how big their belly is, has 6 pack abs underneath that extra layer of fat. The key is to get rid of this fat layer and as a result expose those abs. Sit-ups and crunches will only assist in the actual muscle building of the abs themselves, but without losing that fat layer you won't be seeing any abs at all.
One of the most efficient ways to lose fat (aside from eating correctly) is performing cardio exercise. This could be swimming, running, cycling or even fast-paced walking. A very useful tip is to perform your cardio on an empty stomach when trying to achieve those 6 pack abs. I recommend doing your cardio first thing in the morning before breakfast. When we wake up in the morning our body is in a catabolic state. Catabolism means 'the breaking down' of body tissue, this is the optimum time to perform your fat burning exercises as your body is literally in fat burning mode. In addition to this, because you haven't eaten any food before the exercise your body will break down mostly fat in order to fuel your exercise session rather than food in your system. The idea is to leave our body no choice but to burn mostly fat.- Maintain Your Optimum Fat Burning Heart Rate
When performing any exercise our body decides what resources to use for fuel based on how intensive the exercise is. It all comes down to our heart rate during the exercise. Research shows that our body tends to burn fat optimally at a specific heart rate. This heart is roughly 63% of our maximum heart rate. One is able to maintain this heart rate by slow jogging, fast-paced walking or other similar low intensive activity. One wouldn't think so but this low intensive style exercise is optimal for fat burning! See the end of the article for a resource link which explains exactly how to calculate 63% of your max heart rate.- Perform HIIT To Your Boost Metabolism. 
Aside from low intensive cardio, it's also a good idea to throw in some high intensive interval training (HIIT). This basically involves performing short bursts of intensive activity. An example would be sprinting (running) as fast as you can for half a minute, and then jogging for half a minute, then sprinting for half a minute, then jogging again and simply repeating this process. Although HIIT will not burn as much fat as low intensive cardio during the exercise itself, it is able to boost one's metabolism even after you are have finished the exercise"

Title: b'My Natural Transformation - Thank You For 1,000 Subscribers!'
Description:
b"Today I hit 1,000 subscribers! I can't thank you all enough for the support. I know I say it a lot but that is because it is true. Today I decided to show you guys my transformation. I started this journey at 230lbs in 7th grade. I was never athletic, but when I stepped foot in the gym for the very first time, I knew I found something I would love to do. I lost weight all the way until 9th grade, when I weighed around 150lbs/160lbs. I was skinny. I decided to continue on with what I love to do and this is when I found bodybuilding and the YouTube fitness community. I got educated, I trained smarter, and I dieted smarter. After a few years, I am where I am today. I've been through a lot of transformations, fat to skinny, skinny to skinny fat, then to fit. I hope this video motivates you and helps you continue on your journey. I won't lie sometimes I wanted to quit. Sometimes I fell off track. But then I remembered why I started and that I have you guys all behind me supporting me. We are a team. If you ever need help, motivation, or anything I am always here. Thank you for your support. Title: b'VF Workout 26 - 1 Arm LongCycle Bottom Up Press'
Description:
b"I'm not really into Juggling. It's ok. Interesting to watch, but not serious Strength & Conditioning for me. When training for Kettlebell Sport 18 years ago I could not afford this fun stuff. Actually before even thinking about Kettlebell Sport as a kid I did Kettlebell Juggling routines with my friend to impress girls but that's another story. Later I figured out what was hard core kettlebells and I wanted more. But I never forgot this Juggling and 20+ years later it's still there in my coordination. Still, if you are going to use Juggling for any type of true conditioning or skill building I suggest more simple flips but heavy. Of course be careful, make steady progression starting light, and watch your feet, head and property if you ever try. Best to try outside. This is not my workout really, but I will show you something a little bit before my set that is harder than it looks. For my workout I do a set of 1 Arm LongCycle Bottom Up Press with 24kg/53lb.

Title: b'Pro Mera Sports Beta-Cret Review'
Description:
b'Visit http://www.sixpacksmackdown.com for more recipes, full workouts, supplement reviews and fitness articles.

Pro Mera Sports Beta-Cret Review

I recently tried out a sample packet of ProMera Sports Beta-Cret. The flavor I had was pineapple. Beta Cret is a Micro-Concentrated Pre-Workout Intensifier With Caffeine - 120mg to be exact. Beta-Cret also claims to provide you energy without the crash so I was pretty interested to put those claims to the test.

Highlights:

Beta-Cret did provide a nice energy flow and a "rush" or warming sensation
Pineapple taste was pretty good and mix ability was 10/10
Price is a little higher than I would typically recommend, but if you're not having any luck it may be worth a try.'

Title: b'Como Ganar Masa Muscular Rapidamente - Que Hacer Para Ganar Musculo'
Description:
b'(Visita: http://tinyurl.com/AumentarMusculo )

Para ganar masa muscular de forma r\xc3\xa1pida, les dar\xc3\xa9 unos consejos que le servir\xc3\xa1n de mucho en su camino para ganar masa muscular.
1. Aprendan a comer m\xc3\xa1s. Es as\xc3\xad de sencillo. Si no comen m\xc3\xa1s de lo acostumbrado nunca van a ganar masa muscular. Pero no me refiero a comer todo lo que se te presente, sino saber que cosa comer y que te ayude a ganar masa muscular. Si eres de esas personas a las que les cuesta consumir m\xc3\xa1s comida, tomen licuados caseros. Las calor\xc3\xadas l\xc3\xadquidas no se registran en nuestro cuerpo igual que las s\xc3\xb3lidas lo que quiere decir que es m\xc3\xa1s f\xc3\xa1cil consumir un exceso en forma l\xc3\xadquida que en forma s\xc3\xb3lida. Una buena receta es, 2 cucharadas de mantequilla de man\xc3\xad, 2 tazas de leche enchocolatada, 1 banano. Este licuado contiene aproximadamente 732 calor\xc3\xadas y 25 gramos de prote\xc3\xadna.
2. Consuman prote\xc3\xadnas. Que les quede bien claro. Para ganar masa muscular deben ingerir un gramo de prote\xc3\xadna por libra de peso corporal. Hay muchas comidas altas en prote\xc3\xadna incluyendo huevos, leche, carne, pollo, pescado, nueces, mantequilla de man\xc3\xad etc. 
3. Enf\xc3\xb3quense en los ejercicios compuestos. Los ejercicios compuestos son ejercicios que utilizan m\xc3\xa1s de un grupo muscular. Los ejercicios compuestos m\xc3\xa1s efectivos son. 
Para las piernas. Sentadillas, Prensa, Peso Muerto Piernas Semirigidas.
Para pecho. Press de banco inclinado, fondos.
Para espalda. Remo con barra, peso muerto, jalones al pecho y dominadas.
Para hombros. Press Militar.
Para brazos. Curl con barra, press de banco con agarre cerrado.
Si se enfocan en estos ejercicios van a estimular la mayor cantidad de fibras musculares y por lo tanto aumentar la masa muscular. 
4. Gasten dinero en comida no en suplementos.
La industria de los suplementos est\xc3\xa1 llena de productos inservibles. Los \xc3\xbanicos suplementos que deber\xc3\xadan comprar son prote\xc3\xadna y creatina, y aun as\xc3\xad estos no les van a servir de mucho si no compran la comida que necesitan. Compren granos integrales, fruta, carne, pollo, pescado, leche, nueces, pasta, etc.'

b'How to get sixpack'
Description:
b"My method is not something difficult or expensive, you have to do nothing, literally nothing. Before rush to buy the next genius abs machine or next magic pill, read what I found that really works.

The only reason you don't have 6 pack abs is nutrition industry. There are so many new food offers, they have so good commercials and you can't resist and try every possible food. It is sad to confess that food producers create very tasteful products without care for food ingredients.

To sustain life, your body needs very simple foods. For me simple food is the one that is less processed and much close to its natural condition. For example vegetables, fruits, milk and meat are simple food in my opinion.

How to get a six pack fast

1) Stop eating bad foods -- chocolate bars, muphins, hamburgers, fried vegetables, fried meat, bread, cakes, puddings, pizza etc.

2) Eat food like -- fresh salads (without dressing, add only olive oil, salt and vinegar), baked meat and fish, plain milk, eggs, nuts, small amounts of rice and potatoes, lentils.

3) Try to eat 5-6 small meals per day -- the purpose is to eat every 2-3 hours -- this way you always will have some food in your stomach and there will be no cravings.

4) Don't eat after 18.00 o'clock -- the reason for this is that your body prepares for the night and your metabolism starts to slow down for the night. If you are very hungry in the night it is better to eat one of the mentioned in point 2 foods.

5) Exercise your entire body 3-4 times per week! I mean not only abdominal exercises -- try to perform exercises for every muscle in your body (not literally every 

6) Perform cardio (also called aerobics) like jogging, running, treadmill, intensive walking 1-2 times per week. You can do cardio in separate days or you can add aerobics exercises to your strength training.

7) Feel pleasure! This is very important. If you only think how hungry you are -- this is like to torture yourself. Imagine your future body with six pack abs, imagine how beautiful you'll become. Dream about this moments and your mind will help you to fasten the weight loss. 
Positive thinking always helps.

Now About a mounth later you can already, get the nice ladies and see your six-pack(If you not are really fat)

Thx for watching!"

Title: b'USPA Nationals training 2014: 855lbs for 2 reps PR!'
Description:
b'David "The Beast" Douglas
facebook.com/davidthebeastdouglas.com
Twitter: @BEASTdouglas
Instagram: @davidthebeastdouglas
www.BEASTDOUGLAS.com

855 for 2 reps in prep for USPA Nationals 2014. 308lb Single ply Double PR. We have planned and now things are coming together. Strongest I have ever felt. Instead of going for a heavy single on my last heavy day, i backed it down from 870-880 for 1 to 855 for 2 which proved to be better for my confidence. I again study these videos like football tapes lol and my depth finder needs to drag alittle lower. Even though the 1st one was on target, the 2nd was questionable. Corrections will be made. This is why taping my videos for me is important. I just have alittle fun with the editing lol.Target is 900 at nationals. Not extremely important though because this meet will only be a prep for the Olympia. I want to bring the thought of 1000lbs by Olympia into the picture. That's a more important goal. Next year this 850-900 will be a target for my raw classic which i stand at 775lbs in training. So much to think about over the next couple weeks, but as the waters are calm, i can't even imagine what its going to look like on gameday.. Thank you for all that support! Check it out!

If I was doing the exact same thing every other hockey strength and conditioning coach was doing, then I would be exactly where they are.

Instead, I busted out of just training hockey players in the gym by starting HockeyTrainingPro.com about four years ago. Yes it is more work, but it lets me share great training strategies with goalies from all over the world and I do mean all over -- Mexico, Sweden, Russia, Czech Republic, Australia, UK, Germany, France, China (yes, China), Finland, etc.

You need to do the same to succeed. If you are not where you want to be, then stop doing what you have always done for your hockey training -- clearly it is not working for you.

Let's start with this 'mobility' drill for hockey goalies -- just this one small change could make you a little better today than you were yesterday. 

This exercise did bring tears to my eyes as my hip went into complete spasm, but our instructor kept yelling at us to keep going -- keep going -- then he called some other participants bad names when they stopped so I kept going \xe2\x98\xba 

You give it a try -- if you find it easy, you are either not doing it right OR you do not need to do it (I really doubt this). Start with 10 in each direction -- you can work up to 20 each way -- remember to go slowly!

Doing the little extras adds to your preparation. 

Preparation breeds confidence. Do you think more confidence will help you be a better goalie?

Do you think you would feel more worthy of a spot on the team of your dreams.

Do you think you would actually deserve it?

Me too. Start with this small step to make yourself one day better."

Description:
b"Blog http://road2aesthetics.wordpress.com/

Diet consists of High Fats and High Protein foods, low to no Carbs so still keeping to the keto concept, am not going to change it for a while or till the coach tells me to. Also drinking about 6-8litres a day, fluids must be high due to the high amounts of salts.

Still training different everyday! No one workout is the same. Consists of high reps, low reps, heavy weight and light weights all in the one workout. I am enjoying the new diet and training so I am sure by comp day i should look great and hopefully the best shape I have been in my life.

Title: b'Back Workout - Pull Ups - HomeGym'
Description:
b'In this short video i\xc2\xb4ll show you a part of my back workout.
Pull-ups! One of the most important exercises, you can do for your back and to get a V-shape.
It\xc2\xb4s also an exercise where you don\xc2\xb4t need much equipment. 

If you are able to do 10-12 reps with your bodyweight, you should start with extra weight.
In the first and second part I use 10kg/22lbs extra weight and 5kg/11lbs in the third part.
For the extra weight I use my selfmade belt (for pull-ups and dips)
(If you want to, I\xc2\xb4ll show in another video, how to make a selfmade belt)

- Before I beginn I always warm-up a bit

- Then I start with 3 sets, where the grip is wide and the reps are 8-10
- By the second part my grip is just a litte bit tighter, but also 3 sets with 8-10 reps
- 3rd variation: my grip is tight and neutral, also 3 sets with 8-10 reps

More videos from my home-gym are coming soon!'

Title: b'PULL DOZING PENDLAY STYLE | Wendler 5/3/1 Push Pull C9.2 Cut W10'
Description:
b"Woooo! Big session... and big sessions mean big smiles! Feeling back on top of the training after a nice scoop of ProSupps Hyde... which I won't have another scoop for a while cos god dayum that's some strong shiz.

Wendler 5/3/1 Cycle 9 Week 2 and also Week 10 of my cut. This is my additional push pull session where I focus on Pendlay Rows as a main lift and train upper back alongside an additional bench press. 

For the final set of Pendlay rows I did 117.5kg x 3 reps. Felt good.

Assistance work was V Bar / T Bar rows... decided to give overhand rows a rest this week. Not done these for a while, found that they felt easier. Bare in mind that these are not gunna be crazy strict form when done this heavy but like I have said a few times now, heavy rows get the job done!

Followed up with overhand lat pull downs and then went into bench press.

Managed to hit a 130kg x 1 Bench, failed on 135kg. Hey Ho.

Description: b'http://www.trainerjosh.com\r\n\r\nPush-pull training is an effective means of fat loss programming because it forces the blood in your body to go from one area immediately to another, burning much more calories than normal.
